const ARCHIVE = [{"t":"The West Point Lighthouse","d":"2008-02-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1650","lat":47.6622,"lon":-122.4365,"c":"place","x":"This 1907 group portrait of the Seattle Mountaineers at the West Point Lighthouse was photographed by Asahel Curtis, one of the members.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/mountaineers-westpt-curt-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"Snoqualmie Falls","d":"2008-07-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1660","lat":47.5417,"lon":-121.8378,"c":"place","x":"Snoqualmie Falls appears in full force, probably during a spring runoff.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/snoqualmie-falls-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Coliseum Theatre reborn","d":"2008-08-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1656","lat":47.6105,"lon":-122.3375,"c":"place","x":"In January 1916, Seattle's Coliseum Theatre opened with legends attached. It scarcely mattered that the stage was a bit small for the largest of vaudeville acts for it was claimed to be the largest and most lavish of theatres built not for stage acts but for films. As the legend matured it was also the first. B. Marcus Priteca, Seattle's famed architect of theatres, designed it for one of that tim","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/coliseum_hearst-zeppelin1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle's Front Street","d":"2008-09-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1765","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Looking north from Pioneer Place (square) into the uptown of what was easily the largest town in Washington Territory. This is judged by the 3218 votes cast in the November election of 1884, about one fourth of them by the newly but temporarily enfranchised women.Tacoma, in spite of being then into its second year as the terminus for the transcontinental Northern Pacific Railroad, cast 1663 votes,","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/front-st-fm-occidental-roof-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Warshall's on 2nd Ave","d":"2008-09-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1757","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"At Warshal's Workingman's Store a railroad conductor, for instance, could buy his uniform, get a loan, and/or hock his watch. Neighbors in 1946 included the Apollo Cafe, the Double Header Beer Parlor, and the Circle Theatre, all on Second Avenue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/warshalls-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Freeway Park Dances","d":"2008-09-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2143","lat":47.6109,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place","x":"In the 32 years between Frank Shaw's dedication picture and Jean Sherrard's dance scene, Freeway Park has gained in verdure what it has lost in human use.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/freeway-park-7_4_76-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"First Hill Landmarks","d":"2008-10-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2134","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"A circa 1923 view looks south on Eighth Avenue over Pike Street, at bottom left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/8_pine-lk-s-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Cascade Neighborhood Skyline","d":"2008-10-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2126","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"The scene looks north through a skyline of steeples toward the Cascade neighborhood and Lake Union, ca. 1923.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/8-pine-lk-n-to-lk-union-c23-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"\"Lake Union John\"","d":"2008-10-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1833","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"Pioneer Arthur Denny's son, Orion, took this photo of popularly named Lake Union John and his second wife, Madeline, sometime before the latter's death in 1906.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/john-and-madeline1.jpg"},{"t":"The Potlatch Parade on First Avenue","d":"2008-10-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2100","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"The Moose float heads south on First Avenue at Columbia Street during the 1912 Potlatch parade of fraternal and secret societies. Behind them are Julius Redelsheimer's clothing store and the National Hotel, where daily room rates ran from 50 cents to a dollar.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/moose-float-1st_columb-1912-potlatch-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Moore Theatre","d":"2008-11-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1748","lat":47.6133,"lon":-122.3417,"c":"place","x":"Steel beams clutter a freshly regraded Second Avenue during the 1907 construction of the Moore Theatre. The view looks north toward Virginia Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/moore-theat-construct-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Denny Hill Hotel","d":"2008-11-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1775","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"An early-20th-century scene during the Second Avenue Regrade looks east into its intersection with Virginia Avenue. A home is being moved from harm's way, but the hotel on the hill behind it would not survive the regrade's spoiling. Courtesy of Ron Edge.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/denny-regrade-2nd-virg-ca-19051.jpg"},{"t":"A Pioneer Square Victorian","d":"2008-11-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1802","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"down-and-out Pioneer Square. That unwittingly saved them for later restoration. If memory serves, in 1999, I was invited to visit the sealed hotel to admire its high ceilings, brass fixtures, paneling and hardwood floors with a group of other Allied Arts time travelers. The invitation most likely came through the Samis Foundation, then preparing to restore the building and create 40-odd high-ceili","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/terry-denny-bldg-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Aloha trolley","d":"2008-11-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1836","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Most likely in 1902 Marcus M. Lyter either built or bought his box-style home at the northwest corner of 15th Avenue and Aloha Street. Like many other Capitol Hill addition residences, Lyter's home was somewhat large for its lot.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/15_aloha-lyter-home-ca1902-then1.jpg"},{"t":"A View from Central School tower","d":"2008-11-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1810","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"The home at bottom right looks across Madison Street (out of frame) to Central School. The cleared intersection of Spring Street and Seventh Avenue shows on the right.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/judkins-f-central-school-2-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle's Hippodrome","d":"2008-12-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1794","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The Metropolitan Tract's Hippodrome was nearly new when it hosted the A.F. of L. annual convention in 1913. Courtesy Old Seattle Paperworks.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/hippodrome-1913-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle's Olympic Block","d":"2008-12-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1795","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"With the clue of the ornate Pergola on the right, we may readily figure that we are in Pioneer Square looking south across Yesler Way.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/olympic-block-50s-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Lake Union from Ford plant","d":"2008-12-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1731","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"Photographed from an upper story of the Ford Factory at Fairview Avenue and Valley Street, the evidence of Seattle's explosive boom years can be seen on every shore of Lake Union, ca. 1920. Courtesy of MOHAI","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/fairview-se-lake-union1.jpg"},{"t":"Aurora Overpass","d":"2008-12-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1673","lat":47.65,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place","x":"(Original article title: \"Pedestrian overpass on Seattle's busy Aurora Avenue saves lives\") For me, discovering a forgotten pioneer photograph is an undiluted thrill, but more recent historical photographs, like the one printed here, can also be stirring. This recording from the Seattle Municipal Archive shows a dozen fourth- or fifth-graders from B.F. Day School celebrating the completion of the ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/41st-aurora-pedes-overpass-10-22-36mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Tin Man at Yesler","d":"2009-01-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1738","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"For the first twenty years of his more than 40 years selling tinware and other selected hardware, Zilba Mile's shop looked south across Yesler Way down First Ave. S, then known as Commercial Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/tin-man-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Lake Sammamish: Monohon with Three Os","d":"2009-01-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2089","lat":47.615,"lon":-122.086,"c":"place","x":"With his or her back to the east shore of Lake Sammamish an unidentified photographer recorded this Monohon scene in about 1909, the date suggested by the Eastside Heritage Center, by whose courtesy we use this historical record.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/monohon-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"\"I am blind\"","d":"2009-01-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1710","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place_approx","x":"( Original title: \"An umpire takes abuse, all in fun\" ) With an \"I Am Blind\" sign at his feet and a dunce cap on his head, here sits Northwestern League umpire August Moran in a wicker chair somewhere near the site of his many decisions and transgressions: Dugdale Park's home plate. Augie is covered with flowers and the kind of vegetables one might toss at an umpire before being also thrown from t","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/yesler-way-umpire-day1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle's Arctic Club","d":"2009-01-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1784","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Through its two decades — 1892 to 1913 — at the northeast corner of Cherry Street and Third Avenue, the Seattle Theatre was one of the classiest Seattle venues for legitimate theater as well as variety/vaudeville","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/seattle-theatre-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Green Lake Skaters","d":"2009-02-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1826","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"The thousand and more cutters on Green Lake in this late January 1916 view could not have known that the skating would soon be over, one of the victims of the Big Snow of 1916. Courtesy Fairlook Antiques","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/green-lake-jan-1916-skatersmr1.jpg"},{"t":"'Foodland'","d":"2009-02-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=1914","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"A look down on Wallingford's principal business corner in the fall of 1950","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/foodland-from-school-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Militia at Main Street","d":"2009-02-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2063","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place_approx","x":"The Pacific House, behind the line-up of white-gloved soldiers, might have survived well into the 20th Century were it not destroyed during Seattle's Great Fire of 1889. Courtesy, MOHAI.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/pacific-house-1886-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Occidental's Tourist Hotel","d":"2009-02-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2166","lat":47.5955,"lon":-122.3309,"c":"place","x":"The Lebanon aka Jesse George building at Occidental and Main opened with the Occidental Hotel in 1891. Subsequently the hotel's name was changed first to the Touraine and then to the Tourist. The tower could be seen easily from the railroad stations. It kept the name Tourist until replaced in 1960 with a parking lot.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/tourist-aka-occi-2-main-then-lr1.jpg"},{"t":"Capitol Hill from the Water Tower","d":"2009-03-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2277","lat":47.63,"lon":-122.316,"c":"place","x":"The Volunteer Park water tower was completed in 1907 on Capitol Hill's highest point in aid of the water pressure of its service to the often grand homes of its many nearly new neighbors. The jogging corner of E. Prospect Street and 15th Avenue E. is near the bottom of the Oakes postcard. (Historical Photo courtesy Mike Fairley)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/vol-pk-lk-east-fm-standpipe-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Paramount Theatre Opening Night","d":"2009-03-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=2322","lat":47.6131,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place","x":"As explained in the accompanying story, the cut corner in this search-lighted photo of the \"first-nighters\" lined up for the March 1, 1928 opening of the Seattle Theatre at 9th and Pine was intended. Courtesy Ron Phillips","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/seattle-paramont-theatre-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"Broadening Broadway","d":"2009-03-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3008","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Looking across Capitol Hill's Broadway Avenue during its 1931 adjustments.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/broadway-widening-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Major Millis' Capitol Hill Treasures","d":"2009-03-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3017","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Both the grading on Belmont Avenue and the homes beside it are new in this \"gift\" to Capitol Hill taken from the family album of Major John Millis.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/belmont-and-mercer-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Auburn Sweet Auburn","d":"2009-04-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3020","lat":47.3079,"lon":-122.2295,"c":"place","x":"Auburn's Main Street decorated for its Aug. 14, 1909, \"Good Old Days\" celebration. Photo courtesy of the White River Valley Museum.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/auburn-main-st-lke-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"Great Northern & Mea Culpa","d":"2009-04-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3024","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Looking northwest from the 4th Avenue trestle towards the Great Northern Depot during its early 20th Century construction.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/king-st-station-fm-5th-then-lr1.jpg"},{"t":"Forty-five Years of Freeway","d":"2009-04-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3031","lat":47.59,"lon":-122.268,"c":"place_approx","x":"With great clouds overhead and a landscape 45 years shorter than now, one vehicle – a pickup heading east – gets this part of State Route 520 to itself on a weekday afternoon.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/freeway-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Look Down Into Belltown","d":"2009-05-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3134","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Crowding the bluff above Second Avenue to his left (west) ex-mayor Robert Moran looked northwest into the heart of Belltown from near his home site on top of Denny Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/belltown-moran-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Musical Baptists of Fremont","d":"2009-05-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3249","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place","x":"If I have counted correctly this ca. 1930 Fremont Baptist Orchestra is appointed with three cellos, eleven violins and violas, two saxophones, two clarinets, one coronet, one oboe, one flute and two members who seem to be hiding their instruments.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/fremont-baptist-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Entering the A-Y-P","d":"2009-05-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3452","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"For the four-plus months of the 1909 Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition, the center of commerce and pedestrian energy on University Way moved two blocks south from University Station on Northeast 42nd Street to here, Northeast 40th Street, at left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/ayp-40th-ave-then-lr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Perry Apartments","d":"2009-05-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3458","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"The Perry Apartments is nearly new in \"postcard artist\" M. L. Oakes look at them south on Boren to where it intersects with Madison Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/boren-perry-apts-by-oakes-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The S.S. Suveric visits Pier 56","d":"2009-06-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3463","lat":47.6055,"lon":-122.3424,"c":"place","x":"The S. S. Suveric makes a rare visit to Seattle in 1911. (Historical photo courtesy of Jim Westall)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/06/pier-56-1911-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Childhaven","d":"2009-06-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?page_id=3577","lat":47.6155,"lon":-122.314,"c":"place","x":"\"Users\" of Seattle Day Nursery's recreation patio tip their cups together in 1942. (Historical photo courtesy Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/childhaven-then-lr1.jpg"},{"t":"Real Change","d":"2009-06-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=3640","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"Roughly a century ago, engineer Leo Snow took this candid photograph of a single Native vendor set up at the corner of Second Avenue and Madison Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/06/native-basket-seller-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Mount Vernon Ferry","d":"2009-06-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=3715","lat":48.4201,"lon":-122.3346,"c":"place","x":"In a 1884 election Mt. Vernon surprised La Conner by winning the Skagit County seat. Here, ca. 1890, Mt. Vernon has besides its 800 citizens and one ferry, great prospects. (Photo courtesy Skagit County Historical Museum's Research Library.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/06/mt-vernon-ferry-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"A Little Snow","d":"2009-07-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=3775","lat":47.6203,"lon":-122.3502,"c":"place","x":"Werner Lenggenhager recorded the tracery of the Pacific Science Center's Gothic arches through the promenade that leads to them, marked by the snow of Nov. 19, 1978. (Courtesy Seattle Public Library) Holding my little camera high I took this snapshot repeat of Lenggenhager's romantic snowscape at this year's crowded & hot Folklife Festival. Jack Hansen far left, ca. 1970 Stan James at the 2004 Fol","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/pacific-snow-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Military Discipline at the AYPE","d":"2009-07-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=3808","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"When the Oregon Cadets raised their tents on the Denny Hall lawn in 1909 they were almost venerable. Founded in 1873, the Cadets survive today as Oregon State University's ROTC. Geneticist Linus C. Pauling, twice Nobel laureate, is surely the school's most famous cadet corporal.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/ayp-denny-hall-cadets-campw-mid1.jpg"},{"t":"HOO-HOO and the HBC","d":"2009-07-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=3860","lat":47.63,"lon":-122.258,"c":"place","x":"Above Lake Washington's Union Bay the Hoo-Hoo Building on the left and the Bastion facsimile on the right, were both regional departures from the classical beau arts style, the 1909 AYPE's architectural commonplace. Courtesy John Cooper","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/ayp-hoo-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Pier 70 from the Bay","d":"2009-07-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=3870","lat":47.6207,"lon":-122.354,"c":"place","x":"Pier 70 when it was still Pier 14, ca. 1901, brand new but not yet \"polished.\" Courtesy, Lawton Gowey","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/07/pier-70-cropbx1.jpg"},{"t":"Good Shepherding","d":"2009-08-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4041","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"(click to enlarge) Temporarily untended the Good Shepherd orchard awaits its fate, ca. 1978. The contemporary repeat was \"adjusted\" a few yards to the east to take advantage of this preseason practice by members of the Architects and Engineers Volleyball League. A few of the old orchard's trees survive along the park's western border with Meridian Avenue, far right. Paul Dorpat In 1941 several hun","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/good-shep-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"The Swings of Cowen Park","d":"2009-08-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4012","lat":47.63,"lon":-122.258,"c":"place","x":"This rare glimpse of the rapid Ravenna Creek's fall through Cowen Park was photographed not long before the stream that had \"topped off\" Green Lake into Lake Washington's Union Bay for thousands of years was shut off in 1911. (Photo courtesy of Jim Westall) The emphasis on this \"repeat\" is on the swings more than the place. Much of the Cowen Park ravine was developed into a playfield with dirt bor","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/cowen-pk-swing-then-web11.jpg"},{"t":"First Hill Exceptions","d":"2009-08-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4095","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Looking east on University Street towards Ninth Avenue, ca. 1925, with the Normandie Apartments on the left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/normandie-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Roosevelt Theatre","d":"2009-08-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4135","lat":47.61072,"lon":-122.33532,"c":"addr","x":"The early evening dazzle of the Roosevelt Theatre at 515 Pike Street, probably in 1941.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/roosevelt-theatre-then-1941b1.jpg"},{"t":"The Pantages-Palomar","d":"2009-08-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4142","lat":47.6093,"lon":-122.3398,"c":"place","x":"With the stone federal post office at its shoulder – to the left – and the mostly brick Cobb Building behind, the tiled Pantages Theatre at Third Ave. and University Street gave a glow to the block.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/pantages-theat-3univer-neco1.jpg"},{"t":"\"All Roads Lead to the Dog House\"","d":"2009-09-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4172","lat":47.61861,"lon":-122.34326,"c":"addr","x":"The Dog House at 714 Denny Way was strategically placed at the southern terminus for the Aurora Speedway when it was new in the mid-1930s. (Photo courtesy of Washington State Archive, Bellevue Community College Branch)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/dog-house-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Aurora Speedway, 1932","d":"2009-09-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4244","lat":47.6173,"lon":-122.3478,"c":"place","x":"Here follows a \"now and then\" from Pacific Northwest Mag . for Dec. 18, 1988. Until I find the negative for the \"now\" photo and/or until Jean returns to town to repeat the 1932 view, the scan from the Pacific clipping will have to do for a \"now.\" \"Speedway\" was then ordinarily used as a general name for the oval tracks with bleachers attached that were used for racing mostly open cockpit motorcars","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/aurora-broad-speed-web1.jpg"},{"t":"'Seeing Seattle'","d":"2009-09-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4258","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place_approx","x":"By 1907 it was possible to bump about Seattle on spring seats visiting its favored attractions for a fee. The ride included both a driver and barker – here the swell fellow in the flattop straw hat arranging his pose tending towards profile second from the right. (Pic courtesy Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/seeing-seattle-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Peter Ivanoff's Perpetual Motion Machine","d":"2009-09-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4287","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place","x":"Originally built for the manufacture of a fantastic engine that did not make it beyond its model, the Fremont factory's second owner, Carlos Flohr, used it to build vacuum chambers for protecting telescope lenses. Thirty feet across and made from stainless steel the lens holders were often mistaken for flying saucers. (photo courtesy Kvichak marine Industries.) Still easily identified, the factory","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/ivanoff-fremont-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Armistice Day Parade, Nov. 11, 1918","d":"2009-10-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4351","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"With feet nearly touching the Madison Street Cable Railway's cable slot, five \"happy workers\" squeeze on to the front bumper of an improvised Armistice Day float. (Photo courtesy Grace McAdams)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/armistice-day-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Auto Row","d":"2009-10-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4416","lat":47.621,"lon":-122.355,"c":"place_approx","x":"The brand new N&K Packard dealership at Belmont and Pike in 1909. Thanks to both antique car expert Fred Cruger for identifying as Packards the cars on show here, and to collector Ron Edge for finding them listed at this corner in a 1909 Post-Intelligencer.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/pike-belmont-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Westlake Night Lights","d":"2009-10-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4521","lat":47.62,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Great railroad signs, theatre signs and ranks of neon were still the greatest contributors to night light at 4th and Westlake in 1949.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/westlake-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Portland Now & Then","d":"2009-10-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4533","lat":45.5152,"lon":-122.6784,"c":"place","x":"Amateur photographer George Brown most likely took this view of Portland's 1905 Lewis and Clark Centennial Exposition from the north porch of the Washington State Building. Brown also played clarinet in Wagner's popular concert and marching band, which was probably performing at the Expo. (pic courtesy of Bill Greer) Northwest historian and Portland resident Richard Engeman and Portland author Cla","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/lewis-clark-expo-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Professor Conn","d":"2009-11-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4694","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Courtesy, Lawton Gowey By Paul Dorpat [The feature that follows first appeared in Pacific Northwest Mag. for Nov. 1, 2009.] Normal 0 0 1 341 1949 16 3 2393 11.1282 0 0 0 Normal 0 0 1 51 292 2 1 358 11.1282 0 0 0 The hand-written caption \"Prof Conn family\" can be imperfectly read at the base of this week's historical subject. I know Conn not for his professing but for his photographs. His views aro","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/prof-conn-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"One STURDY BRIDGE","d":"2009-11-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4819","lat":47.63623,"lon":-122.35704,"c":"addr","x":"Walter Ross Baumes Willcox, the architect who planned this 1911 Arboretum aqueduct, went on to design another city landmark made of reinforced concrete and ornamental bricks: the 1913 Queen Anne Boulevard retaining wall. (Courtesy, Museum of History and Industry) Built in line with Lynn Street, the trestle through Washington Park is little worse for wear after taking many direct hits from trucks a","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/arboretum-bridge-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"North Edgewater","d":"2009-11-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4817","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Postcard photographer M. L. Oakes has captioned his subject \"Edgewater looking N.E.\" and yet many, perhaps most, of those now living in these blocks will, I'd bet, have no inkling that they live in Edgewater. Some will put themselves in Fremont, others in Wallingford. Only a few will prefer Freeford or Wallingmont. In spite of this confusion, we thank Oakes, for it is rare indeed to find a histori","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/edgewater-nef-40-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Friends of the Market","d":"2009-11-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4860","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.34039,"c":"addr","x":"Depression-time customers examine the eggs and plucked hens in the Market's North Arcade.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/pmarket-n-arcade-30s-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Sprague Hotel on Yesler","d":"2009-11-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4894","lat":47.60176,"lon":-122.32395,"c":"addr","x":"The Sprague Hotel at 706 Yesler Way was one of many large structures –hotels, apartments and duplexes, built on First Hill to accommodate the housing needs of the city's manic years of grown between its Great Fire in 1889 and the First World War. Photo courtesy Lawton Gowey","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/sprague-hotel-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Naramore Fountain","d":"2009-12-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=4990","lat":47.6066,"lon":-122.3304,"c":"place","x":"Art Critic Sheila Farr describes George Tsutakawa's fountain at 6th and Seneca as showing a \"style that lends modernism with philosophical and formal elements of traditional Asian art, a combination that became emblematic of the Northwest school.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/tsutakawa-1967-then1.jpg"},{"t":"English Gardens at Chittenden Locks","d":"2009-12-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5215","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place_approx","x":"Looking west from the roof of the still standing testing lab, the Lock's Administration Building (from which this photograph was borrowed) appears on the left, and the district engineer's home, the Cavanaugh House (still standing) on the center horizon. (Photo courtesy Army Corps of Engineers at Chittenden Locks)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/locks-english-gardens-1916-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Fifth and Westlake","d":"2009-12-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5274","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"The Seattle Electric Company's sprawling \"campus\" for trolleys once covered most of the two blocks between Fifth and Seventh Avenues and Pine and Olive Streets. By 1910 trolleys were being parked and repaired in new barns at places like Fremont, Lower Queen Anne, and Georgetown.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/5th-ave-car-barns-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"\"Testing Cedar River Water\"","d":"2010-01-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5558","lat":47.422,"lon":-121.77,"c":"place","x":"Carolyn Marr, Museum of History and Industry librarian and Anders Wilse expert, answers the joking caption on Councilman Reinhard's pant leg with another example. \"Wilse had a wry sense of humor. In one photo he took during the Great Northern Railroad construction project, a group of 4 men sit around a table playing cards with revolvers and glasses of liquid. He wrote on the photo ‘A Merry Christm","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/testing-cedar-riv-water-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle Now and Then:  A Wallingford Restoration","d":"2010-01-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5606","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"4719 Thackeray Place NE. The 1938 WPA tax photo. (Courtesy Washington State Archive, Bellevue Community College Branch) Here's a happy story now increasingly told throughout Seattle. The names and places vary but the story is the same, and restoration is always in the title. In this instance Claudia Levi purchased the Wallingford home seen in the second photograph (below), with a mind to restoring","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/claudias-home-1938-web1.jpg"},{"t":"The Swedish Baptists","d":"2010-01-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5679","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.314,"c":"place","x":"The Ballard Public Library in 1903-4, and here the Swedish Baptist Church at 9th and Pine, 1904-5, were architect Henderson Ryan's first large contracts after the 20 year old southerner first reached Seattle in 1898. Later he would also design both the Liberty and Neptune Theatres, the latter still projecting films in the University District. (Photo courtesy Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/swedish-bapt-9-pine-mr41.jpg"},{"t":"Built Around the Organ","d":"2010-01-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5739","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place_approx","x":"Seattle Architect Paul Henderson Ryan designed the Liberty Theatre around the first of many subsequent Wurlitzer organs used for accompanying silent films in theatres \"across the land\". The Spanish-clad actor-dancers posed on the stage apron are most likely involved in a promotion for a film – perhaps Don Q, Son of Zorro (1925) or Douglas Fairbanks' The Gaucho (1929) that also played at the Libert","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/liberty-theatre-interior-then1.jpg"},{"t":"A Footprint of Love","d":"2010-01-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5865","lat":47.623,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Part of the roofline of Cascade School - the school that named the neighborhood - rises above a tight ensemble of workers homes in 1937-8.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/minor-thomas-p-patch-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Surgeon Taylor's Blockhouse","d":"2010-02-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5732","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"In late 1855 the citizens of Seattle with help from the crew of the Navy sloop-of-war Decatur built a blockhouse on the knoll that was then still at the waterfront foot of Cherry Street. The sloop's physician John Y. Taylor drew this earliest rendering of the log construction.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/taylors-block-house-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Fox Garage","d":"2010-02-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=5961","lat":47.616,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"With her or his back to the Medical-Dental Building an unidentified photographer took this look northeast through the intersection of 6th and Olive Way about five years after the Olive Way Garage first opened in 1925.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/fox-garage-6-olive-thenmr1.jpg"},{"t":"Queen Anne Theatre","d":"2010-02-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6097","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"Long thought to be an early footprint for West Seattle's Admiral Theatre, this charming brick corner was actually far away on another Seattle Hill. Courtesy, Southwest Seattle Historical Society.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/queen-anne-theatre-thenmr1.jpg"},{"t":"Horse Meat Anytime","d":"2010-02-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6142","lat":47.60881,"lon":-122.34065,"c":"addr","x":"Eating a horse was considered less disturbing during the Second World War when beef was rationed.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/montana-horse-meat-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"A Secret Crash","d":"2010-03-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6174","lat":47.58294,"lon":-122.32148,"c":"addr","x":"A few minutes out on its first test a still secret and as yet unnamed B-29 turned back for Boeing Field, and did not make it. The view looks southwest from Walker Street to the severed north wall of the Frye meat-packing plant at 2203 Airport Way South. (compliments The Museum of History and Industry, the P-I Collection.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/b29-frye-crash2-wb11.jpg"},{"t":"The Orpheum Theatre","d":"2010-03-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6254","lat":47.62,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Thanks to Pacific reader John Thomas for sharing this photograph recorded by his father in 1927. It looks north across Times Square to the almost completed Orpheum Theatre. Fifth Avenue is on the left, and Westlake on the right.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/orpheum-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"City Archives Silver Anniversary","d":"2010-03-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6366","lat":47.60331,"lon":-122.33027,"c":"addr","x":"The clerk in the city's old Engineering Vault attends to its records. Now one of many thousands of images in the Seattle Municipal Archives, this negative is dated Jan. 30, 1936. (Check out http://www.cityofseattle.net/cityarchives/ to see more.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/city-archives-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Freedman Building","d":"2010-03-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6405","lat":47.5985,"lon":-122.323,"c":"place","x":"The Freedman Building on Maynard Avenue was construction soon after the Jackson Street Regrade lowered the neighborhood and dropped Maynard Avenue about two stories to its present grade in Chinatown. (Photo courtesy Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/freedman-building-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Retail at 2nd & Pine","d":"2010-04-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6428","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Looking south from Pine Street down the wide Second Avenue in 1911, then Seattle's growing retail strip and parade promenade.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/2nd-pine-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Float and the Tenement","d":"2010-04-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6463","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.345,"c":"place","x":"This Denny Regrade subject looks northwest across Blanchard Street towards Second Avenue in 1911. Posing for the unnamed photographer are both the \"caste\" in the float and some residents in windows of the Blanchard Apt. across the street. (Pix courtesy of Michael Maslan Vintage Posters, Photographs, Postcards & Ephemera.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/2nd-and-blanchard-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Weights and Measures","d":"2010-04-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/?p=6592","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"A winter of 1918 inspection of some captured scales on Terrace Street. The view looks east from near 4th Avenue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/weights-condemned-terrace-st-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Bound for Ballard","d":"2010-04-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-bound-for-ballard/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"A Seattle Street and Sewer Department photographer recorded this scene in front of the nearly new City-County Building in 1918. The view looks west from 4th Avenue along a Jefferson Street vacated in this block except for the municipal trolley tracks. (Photo courtesy Seattle Municipal Archive)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/city-county-bldg-then1.jpg"},{"t":"6th and Marion","d":"2010-05-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-6th-and-marion/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place_approx","x":"The city's regrading forces reached Sixth Avenue and Marion Street in 1914. A municipal photographer recorded this view on June 24. Soon after, the two structures left high here were lowered to the street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/6thmarion-regrade-1914-then1.jpg"},{"t":"9th and Yesler","d":"2010-05-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-9th-and-yesler/","lat":47.605,"lon":-122.322,"c":"place","x":"Harborview Hospital takes the horizon in this 1940 recording. That year, a hospital report noted that \"the backwash of the depression\" had overwhelmed the hospital's outpatient service for \"the country's indigents who must return periodically for treatment.\" Built in 1931 to treat 100 cases a day, in 1939 the hospital \"tries bravely to accommodate 700 to 800 visits a day.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/830-yesler-way-b-1940-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Lewis Whittelsey's Survey","d":"2010-05-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-lewis-whittelseys-survey/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Looking north from Seneca Street on Third Avenue during its regrade in 1906.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/3rd-no-fm-seneca-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Green Lake Theatre, 1947","d":"2010-05-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-green-lake-theatre-1947/","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Looking north on Woodlawn Avenue Northeast through its intersection with Northeast 71st Street, the scene was photographed in 1947. Many of the structures in this East Green Lake business district survive, although not all. Some, like the closed Green Lake Theater, have been remodeled.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/greenlake-theatre-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Neely Mansion","d":"2010-05-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-neely-mansion-kent/","lat":47.3047,"lon":-122.1797,"c":"place","x":"(Click to Enlarge) The Neely family mansion - or big farmhouse - was built in the mid-1890s east of Auburn near a ferry crossing on the Green/White River. (Courtesy Neely Mansion Association.) The restored big home is located at 12303 Auburn-Black Diamond Road, just east of the Highway 18 Auburn-Black Diamond Road Exist. For more information call (253) 833-9409. (Now photo by Karen Meador) When I ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/1894-neely-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Lost Landmarks at Pier 51","d":"2010-06-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-lost-landmarks-at-pier-51/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place","x":"Thanks to Seattle Public Library librarian John LaMont for finding Werner Lenggenhager's 1961 record of the stern-wheeler Skagit Belle waiting between","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/skagit-belle-pier-51-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The View from Belvedere Viewpoint","d":"2010-06-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-view-from-belvedere-viewpoint/","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"The view of Seattle from West Seattle's Admiral Way ca. 1934-35.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/seattle-fm-w-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle City Light Steam Plant","d":"2010-06-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-seattle-city-light-steam-plant/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"A municipal photographer recorded this view across Eastlake Avenue of the charming Lake Union Water Power Auxiliary Plant on the left, and on the right the first section of the Lake Union Steam Plant in 1917.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/lk-union-steam-1917-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"\"This Place Matters\"","d":"2010-06-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-this-place-matters/","lat":47.581,"lon":-122.408,"c":"place","x":"One of about a dozen photographs commissioned by the first owners of Fir Lodge, the Bernards. The Lodge is on the left, behind the lead team of white horses. The Bernards did not let us know with their own caption why about a dozen white-clad women are posing in the Seattle Transit vehicle on what now is part of Alki Ave. SW. (Photo Courtesy Log House Museum)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/06/homestead-horses-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"A View Across First Hill","d":"2010-07-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-a-view-across-first-hill/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Looking northwest across a bench in the rise of First Hill, ca. 1887-88. The photographer was probably one of three. George Moore, David Judkins and Theodore Peiser were the local professionals then most likely to leave their studios and portrait work to take this shot from near the corner of Seventh Avenue and Jefferson Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/7_jefferson-then1.jpg"},{"t":"the Pike Street Hill Climb","d":"2010-07-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-pike-street-hill-climb/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"This is one of hundreds of images showing how Seattle changed between the early 1960s and the mid-1980s, recorded by Frank Shaw who lived in an apartment on Lower Queen Anne Hill. The Pike Place Public Market and the waterfront were two subjects he often visited.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/pike-hillclimb-1976-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"Pike Pier","d":"2010-07-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-pike-pier/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.368,"c":"place","x":"In the gaggle of vessels hugging the sides of the Pike Street pier it is the 1200-ton wooden steamship Santa Ana that shows a full profile. She may be backing out of the slip between the Pike Street and Schwabacher's piers. However, there is a chop on Elliot bay and the black smoke from her stack may be pushed east by a breeze off of Elliott Bay. Perhaps the Santa Ana is coming home from Alaska to","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/pike-fm-57-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"The Evelyn May in the Belltown Ravine","d":"2010-07-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-evelyn-may-in-the-belltown-ravine/","lat":47.6147,"lon":-122.3464,"c":"place","x":"(DOUBLE CLICK to ENLARGE) A rare look into the \"Belltown Ravine\" circa 1900. The scene, which also shows the sloop Evelyn May cradled on shore, was photographed from an offshore railroad trestle. (Coutesy, Ron Edge) The ravine was filled long ago, and the rough but often charmed neighborhood of squatters' sheds is now spread with a campus of condos and other attractions protected behind glass wall","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/evelynmay-beltwnravweb21.jpg"},{"t":"The Bell Street Overpass","d":"2010-08-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-bell-street-overpass/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Of all the trestles constructed to cross Alaskan Way the longest-lived is the overpass that reaches Colman Dock, the ferry terminal, on Marion Street. The second oldest is this one on Bell Street. The bridge on Marion was always only for pedestrians. The bridge on Bell was for many years used also by trucks, cars, and in the beginning wagons as well. Actually, there have been many other overpasses","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/bell-st.-bridge-then-web-500x300.jpg"},{"t":"The Eaton Apartments","d":"2010-08-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-eaton-apartments/","lat":47.6212,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"Looking kitty-corner across Thomas Street and Second Ave. North to the Eaton Apartments, ca. 1940. It is a rare recording of Seattle Center acres before their make-over for the 1962 Century 21. (Please Click to Enlarge All the Illustrations) Jean Sherrard visited the intersection during the recent playing of the Folklife Festival, and caught folk-jazz artist Eric Apoe, with his guitar, leaving the","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/bonita-vista-apt-2-thomaswe1.jpg"},{"t":"Ridgemont Theatre","d":"2010-08-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-ridgemont-theatre/","lat":47.689,"lon":-122.355,"c":"place","x":"In 1947, the Ridgemont Theater at Greenwood Avenue and North 78th Street was already 28 years old. (With this subject and the rest CLICK TO ENLARGE.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/ridgemont-theatre-ca47-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Seattle Speed Bowl","d":"2010-08-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-seattle-speed-bowl/","lat":47.565,"lon":-122.3,"c":"place","x":"The Seattle Speed Bowl, which was actually in what is now Edmonds, opened for midget racing in 1936.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/aurora-speed-bowl-web1.jpg"},{"t":"A Farm near Lake Union","d":"2010-08-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-2/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"It appears that pioneer photographer Henry Peterson has recorded Joseph Raber posing with his family in their garden at the south end of Lake Union in 1882.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/boren-farm-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Colman Dock","d":"2010-09-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-colman-dock/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The modern tower of the new deco-styled Colman Dock is seen from the Railroad Avenue (Alaskan Way) overpass soon after the remodeled dock's completion in 1937.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/colman-dock-frnt-faced-then21.jpg"},{"t":"The Central Bus Terminal","d":"2010-09-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-central-bus-terminal/","lat":47.6147,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place_approx","x":"The spire of Gethsemane Church peeks above the tiled roof of a new Central Terminal in 1928. The terminal is nearly new in the photo by Asahel Curtis. The sidewalk awning blocks the full name of the eatery there. On the authority of a 1928 Polk City Directory, it's Terminal Cafe.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/bus-terminal-mr-thenx1.jpg"},{"t":"Dexter Horton's Ruin","d":"2010-09-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-dexter-hortons-ruins/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"After the city's big fire of 1889, its first bank, Dexter Horton's at First Avenue South and Washington Street, although gutted, was still secure in its back-wall vault -both used and guarded.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/dex-hort-bnk-89-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Union Bay Houseboat","d":"2010-09-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-union-bay-boathouse/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"Somewhere along the University of Washington's Union Bay shoreline, when Lake Washington was still at its original - although seasonally varying - elevation. (Courtesy Dan Kerlee) [With the illustrations above and below you should generally click you mouse TWICE – 2-times – on them to best enlarge the image to a size most easily read.] When the photo postcard purveyor M. L. Oakes selected this hou","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/x-oakes-houseboat-uw-web1.jpg"},{"t":"The Top of Queen Anne","d":"2010-10-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-top-of-queen-anne/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Facing First Avenue North, north of Howe Street in 1889-90, these pioneer homes did not survive the wave of Seattle's booming growth through the 1890s. They were soon replaced with the \"better homes and gardens\" that are still familiar on top of Queen Anne Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/queen-anne-top-then1.jpg"},{"t":"East on Pine","d":"2010-10-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-east-on-pine/","lat":47.613,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place_approx","x":"Only an extended arm of one pedestrian shows at the bottom-left corner of the historical scene.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/pine-4th-ca15-langmr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"the 45th Street Viaduct","d":"2010-10-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-45th-street-viaduct/","lat":47.662,"lon":-122.274,"c":"place","x":"On June 8, 1939 a photographer from the city's public works department looked east over the work-in-progress on the 45th Street viaduct and the nurtured wet lands of Union Bay to Laurelhurst. What since the mid 1950s has been the University Village was then still acreage given for the most part to nurseries. (Municipal Archive.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/45st-viaduct-5-8-39-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Fireboat Duwamish","d":"2010-10-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-fireboat-duwamish/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"The nearly new fireboat Duwamish holds to her Firehouse No. 5 at the foot of Madison Street, circa 1912.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/duwamish-fireboat-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Startup Baptists","d":"2010-11-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-startup-baptists/","lat":47.9128,"lon":-122.0985,"c":"place_approx","x":"In 1911 the street in Startup was still years away from development as part of Highway 2 to Stevens Pass. The view looks due east from 364th Avenue Southeast to Mount Nina and Zeke's Peak, which contribute some of the \"water power\" for the spectacular Wallace Falls, which can be seen from the highway.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/startup-wa-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"– Associated Poultry on Fried Chicken Way","d":"2010-11-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-associated-poultry-on-fried-chicken-way/","lat":47.718,"lon":-122.294,"c":"place","x":"Associated Poultry at 90th and Bothell Way (Lake City Way) allowed one to purchase \"direct\" the same tasty fryers served at the nearby Coon Chicken Inn. (Courtesy of M.L.Graham Collection) A few years following the razing of the fryer factory in 1950-51, a Shell Station was built at this northwest corner of NE 90th St. and Lake City Way. That too has been replaced by what Jean Sherrard found there","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/xassoct-poultry-ext.-then1-500x367.jpg"},{"t":"The Medical Dental Building","d":"2010-11-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-medical-dental-building/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place","x":"Looking south from Virginia Street on 5th Avenue to the new Medical Dental Building, ca. 1925.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/med-dental-blldg-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Street Photography","d":"2010-11-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-street-photography/","lat":47.5673,"lon":-122.6329,"c":"place_approx","x":"With a cacophony of marquees and merchant come-ons behind them, West Seattleite Virginia Slate (right), 22, and nephew Jerry Johnson, 8, are caught by a candid street photographer strolling north along the west sidewalk of Seattle's Fourth Avenue between Pike and Pine streets in mid-1945.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/candid-4th-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Gothic Row on Western","d":"2010-12-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-gothic-row-on-western/","lat":47.61306,"lon":-122.3478,"c":"addr","x":"This row of Victorian homes on Western Avenue did not make it to the 1937 inventory of King County's taxable structures. They were, for some unrecorded reason, destroyed earlier.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/gothic-row-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Fort Lawton Barracks","d":"2010-12-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-fort-lawton-barracks/","lat":47.658,"lon":-122.418,"c":"place","x":"The prolific postcard producer Ellis probably recorded this view of Ft. Lawton's new barracks soon after they were constructed in 1942. This was four years after the Army offered to sell its fort back to the city for one dollar, but the city refused for want of depression-time funds to maintain it.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/ft-lawton-barracks-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"'Threading the Bead' Between Magnolia and Ballard","d":"2010-12-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-threading-the-bead-between-magnolia-and-ballard/","lat":47.65,"lon":-122.397,"c":"place","x":"After considering Shilsholia, which sounds similar to the native name for this waterway and means \"threading the bead,\" Lawtonwood got its name by vote of its residents in 1925.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/lawtonwood-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Labor Temple","d":"2010-12-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-labor-temple/","lat":47.616,"lon":-122.3458,"c":"place","x":"\"In what was then a neighborhood of hotels and apartments Seattle's Labor Temple opened in 1905 at the northeast corner of 6th Avenue and University Street. (Pic courtesy Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/labor-temple-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Savoy Hotel","d":"2011-01-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-savoy-hotel/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Mid-block on the east side of Second Avenue between Seneca and University Streets, The Savoy, in seems, had its windows arranged to allow its name to be stamped with big block letters on its north and south facades.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/hotel-savoy-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle City Light","d":"2011-01-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-seattle-city-light/","lat":47.6075,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place_approx","x":"Considerably smaller than hoped for, City Light's headquarters at Third and Madison were dedicated in 1935 with an electric appliance showroom on the main floor and a 240 seat auditorium for promotions and lectures on \"the better uses of electricity.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/city-light-newthen-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Central Business District from Harborview","d":"2011-01-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-central-business-district-from-harborview/","lat":47.605,"lon":-122.322,"c":"place","x":"The photographer of this fresh look into the business district's north end was most likely from the Post-Intelligencer. The style of grease pencil marking left near the edge of the original negative was typical of the P-I.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/harborview-to-cbd-c1931x1.jpg"},{"t":"Harborview from Smith Tower","d":"2011-01-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-harborview-from-smith-tower/","lat":47.6021,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place","x":"Sighting east from the Smith Tower in 1930 to the part of First Hill called Profanity Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/harborview-courth-5-13-301.jpg"},{"t":"Lake Union from Smith Tower","d":"2011-01-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-lake-union-from-smith-tower/","lat":47.6021,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place","x":"The historical look north from the Smith Tower towards Lake Union was most likely photographed by Albert Price, a name that survives with the Price Photo Digital Service in the Roosevelt neighborhood.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/lake-union-fm-smith-tower-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"A New Fourth Avenue aka City Within a City","d":"2011-02-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-a-new-fourth-avenue-aka-city-within-a-city/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"With remarkable haste the first distinguished buildings of the Metropolitan Tract we constructed between 1908 and 1910 on what had been the original campus for the University of Washington. Pix courtesy Lawton Gowey.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/metro-cobb-white-then-times1.jpg"},{"t":"Piner's Point and Plummer's Bay","d":"2011-02-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-piners-point-and-plummers-bay/","lat":47.578,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place","x":"An unnamed photographer here looks down from Beacon Hill to the flooded mudflats south of Seattle's Pioneer Place neighborhood either very late in December 1883 or, more likely, early in 1884. The pilings in the bay that are not useful trestles are land speculators freelance markings meant to set precedents of ownership to the tideflats.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/gas-cove-ca84-fm-beacon-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Waterfront Park Fountain","d":"2011-02-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-waterfront-park-fountain/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"James FitzGerald's Waterfront Fountain was Helen Harrington Schiff's gift to the city in memory of her parents, Edward M. and Margaret J. Harrington. At 16-1/2 feet high and 21 feet long, the bronze fountain puts on a good show.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/waterfront-pk-fount-9-27-1974-thenb1.jpg"},{"t":"Romans' St. James from the Great Northern Tower","d":"2011-02-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-romans-st-james-from-the-great-northern-tower/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"When completed in 1907 St. James Cathedral sparkled atop First Hill. This view of it was photographed early in its life from the tower of the Great Northern Depot","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/st-james-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Wallingford Fisticuffs","d":"2011-03-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-wallingford-fisticuffs-2/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Stan Stapp, publisher of the North Central Outlook, recorded this fistfight in the spring of 1952. In this instance the story came to him. The fists were thrown for the half-witted amusement of other boys soon after Lincoln High recessed for the day. The scene is on North 42nd Street just east of Ashworth Avenue North.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/lincoln-h.s.-fistfight-then-mr--500x342.jpg"},{"t":"Madrona Park – End of the Line","d":"2011-03-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-madrona-park-end-of-the-line/","lat":47.613,"lon":-122.287,"c":"place","x":"Thankfully, the original photo for this early view of Madrona Park has its date, December 18, 1892 written on the back. (Photo Courtesy, Ron Edge)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/madrona-hotel-1892-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Lowman and Hanford","d":"2011-03-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-lowman-and-hanford/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"For more than half a century Lowman and Hanford was an active printing business in the Pioneer Square neighborhood. This view looks southeast through the intersection of First Avenue and Cherry Street, on the left, to the building row still standing along the eastern edge of Pioneer Place – or Square.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/lowman-hanford-1stcherry-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Floating Bridge Inauguration","d":"2011-03-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-floating-bridge-inauguration/","lat":47.63,"lon":-122.258,"c":"place","x":"After twenty years of debate about whether to build it and where and how, the first bridge across Lake Washington took 18 months and a few days from ground breaking to accepting its first tolls from drivers happy for the short cut. (Photo courtesy Washington State Archive.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/mercer-isl-bridge-opening-crowdmr1.jpg"},{"t":"Monty's Stump","d":"2011-04-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-montys-stump/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"Ambrose Kiehl, the engineer who first surveyed and laid out Fort Lawton, survey's the fort from the helpful prospect of a tall cedar stump. Behind him is the inlet between Shilshole and Salmon bays, circa 1898. (Photo courtesy University of Washington Libraries, Special Collections.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/stump-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Gather Ye Rose Buds While Ye May","d":"2011-04-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-zoo-story/","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"When the Phinney (of the ridge) family began developing their country estate in 1889, plans included a small zoo, a hotel, a stone chapel (Episcopalian) a boat house on Green Lake, a hunters lodge beside it, a mansion for the family, a bandstand and this green house. Courtesy, Seattle Municipal Archive.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/green-house-woodprk-early-w1.jpg"},{"t":"The Abiding Smith Tower","d":"2011-04-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-abiding-smith-tower/","lat":47.6021,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place","x":"When the Smith Tower was completed in 1914 to its claimed 42 stories, the \"old town\" choice for its footprint was thought by many to be a mistake, for Seattle's business district had by then begun its big move north.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/gn-pan-cbdca19291.jpg"},{"t":"The Public Safety Building","d":"2011-05-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-public-safety-building/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"It is a gratifying moment when construction photographs of our civic landmarks surface. This one dates ca. 1908, and it is shared by the Seattle Municipal Archive. The Terrace Street steps to \"Profanity Hill\" are on the far left and the old King County Court House tops the horizon. Yesler Way is on the right.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/public-safety-bldg-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Looking North on 3rd","d":"2011-05-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-looking-north-on-3rd/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Looking north on Third Avenue and thru its intersection with Cherry Street, circa 1903. Courtesy MOHAI","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/3rd-n-thru-cherry-ca1.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Front Street Show Strip","d":"2011-05-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-front-street-show-strip/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"By 1881 Seattle was the largest city in Washington Territory, and the richest too. This strip of distinguished facades was the city's best evidence of its successes.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/front-st1.jpg"},{"t":"Madison Trolley Accident","d":"2011-05-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-madison-trolley-accident/","lat":47.6168,"lon":-122.336,"c":"place_approx","x":"This image is used courtesy of Ron Edge. Ron is also the curator of the helpful 1912 Baist map at dorpatsherrardlomont that was featured in a recent Pacific. He purchased the original negative for this scene, not from the Webster and Stevens Studio that made it, nor the Seattle Times that ordered it, but rather from an on-line auction.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/trolly-accidn-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"A Saved Victorian – The Brewer House","d":"2011-05-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-a-saved-victorian-the-brewer-house/","lat":47.6306,"lon":-122.3132,"c":"place","x":"The corner Victorian at 21st Avenue and Columbia Street when it was nearly new ca. 1892. Courtesy Raymond & Zia Hachiya","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/brewer-house-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"We Come in Peace","d":"2011-06-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-we-come-in-peace/","lat":47.6168,"lon":-122.336,"c":"place_approx","x":"The recently deceased artist Victor Lygdman recorded this \"meeting\" while exploring the construction site for Century 21 in 1961.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/we-come-in-peace-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Where's the Beef?","d":"2011-06-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-wheres-the-beef/","lat":47.65,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place_approx","x":"With back to Valley Street, an unnamed photographer records the night lights of what is a nearly new Dag's Drive-In, where, its celebrated back-lighted reader board explains, 19-cent Beefy Boy Burgers are served with \"aba cadabra.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/dags-night-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Green Lake Swimmers","d":"2011-06-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-green-lake-swimmers/","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"This record of the southwest corner of Green Lake is another scene pulled from the large Webster and Stevens collection at the Museum of History and Industry. \"W&S\" was the contracted photography studio used by The Seattle Times for many years and it is possible that this subject first appeared in this paper a century ago.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/green-lk-swim-mrcrop-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Biker's Choice","d":"2011-06-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-bikers-choice/","lat":47.63,"lon":-122.258,"c":"place_approx","x":"The building of tax, license, and gift supported bike paths in the late 1890s catered to a local biking enthusiasm that in 1901, it is estimated, involved ten thousand cyclists in a Seattle of about 100,000 citizens. (Photo courtesy of Michael Maslan)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/bike-trail-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Colman Dock and the H.B. Kennedy","d":"2011-07-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-colman-dock-and-the-h-b-kennedy/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"This circa 1915 waterfront scene at Colman Dock show pairs of steamers, towers and smokestacks. Far left is the singular Hogue Building at 2nd Ave. and Cherry Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/rebuilt-colman-d-fwater-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"War Bonds on The Ave","d":"2011-07-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-war-bonds-on-the-ave/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.314,"c":"place","x":"Beginning in 1942 and thru the duration of World War Two, 45th Street in the University District was regularly blocked for rallies pushing the sale of War Bonds. (Historical photo courtesy of the University Book Store.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/45th-buy-bonds-ww2mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Antique Alki Swimwear","d":"2011-07-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-antique-alki-swimwear/","lat":47.5807,"lon":-122.4079,"c":"place","x":"A century ago the Seattle Parks Department built the large Alki Beach Municipal Bathhouse seen here behind the four posing flappers. None of the woman are identified. The bathhouse was a city-wide magnet for summer fun with thousands often swarming this beach on weekends.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/alki-beach-4-women-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"3rd and Pine","d":"2011-07-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-3rd-and-pine/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"The steps, left of center, and above the steps the one-block long counterbalanced trolley connect to the front door of the Washington Hotel at the top of Denny Hill. The unnamed photographer looks across Pine Street and north on Third Avenue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/3rd-pine-low-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"3rd and Pine 1917","d":"2011-07-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-3rd-and-pine-1917/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.345,"c":"place","x":"Where last week the old Washington Hotel looked down from the top of Denny Hill to the 3rd Ave. and Pine St. intersection, on the left, here the New Washington Hotel, left of center and one block west of the razed hotel, towers over the still new Denny Regrade neighborhood in 1917. (Historical photo courtesy of Ron Edge)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/3rd-pine-wpole-mrthen1.jpg"},{"t":"Denny Knoll's Death Knell","d":"2011-08-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-denny-knolls-death-knell/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"Looking north from Seneca into the Fourth Avenue Regrade of 1907 as it cuts through Denny Knoll, home of the original University of Washington campus. (Photo courtesy Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/4th-regrad-nfmsenecamr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle Then & Now: The GRANITE FALLS STATION","d":"2011-08-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-then-now-the-granite-falls-station/","lat":48.0876,"lon":-121.9712,"c":"place","x":"Above: The stately Granite Falls Railroad Station was built for both the Everett & Monte Cristo Railway Line, and a political payoff. (Courtesy, Granite Falls Historical Society.) Below: From the prospect of the unnamed historical photographer, the site of the now long gone Granite Falls station has been returned to nature. (Now photo by Fred Cruger) (Note: Click the photos to enlarge them. For ma","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/granite-falls-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Within Woodland Park","d":"2011-08-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-within-woodland-park/","lat":47.65,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place","x":"Above: The fitting name for Woodland Park was especially enjoyed in its early years before Aurora Avenue was cut through it. This view looks south from a since razed pedestrian bridge that was built a few yards south of N. 59 th Street, at the park's northern boundary. (Courtesy, Municipal Archives.) Below: To repeat the historic photograph's prospect, Jean Sherrard used a ten-foot pole and stood ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/woodland-pk-bridge-then-web1.jpg"},{"t":"Fifth Avenue Parades","d":"2011-08-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-fifth-avenue-parades/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place","x":"An unnamed photographer looks south on 5th Avenue thru Times Square during the final stages of an early American Legion sponsored Independence Day parade. After nearly two hours of marching, one-by-one the units were disbanded one block behind the photographer at 5th and Virginia Street. (Courtesy Lawton Gowey) NOW: On Tuesday, July 5th last, Jean Sherrard and his ten-foot camera pole entered the ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/amer-legion-parade-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Heroic John McGraw","d":"2011-09-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-heroic-john-mcgraw/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.345,"c":"place","x":"One of Seattle's early examples of honorific public art, caste in bronze, Gov. John McGraw looks over Times Square. Behind him is the freshly lowered and nearly vacant Denny Regrade. The large and all wood Hotel Rainbow on the left barely survived the regrade.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/mcgraw-statue-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Luna Park Entrance","d":"2011-09-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-luna-park-entrance/","lat":47.5856,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"Clumsily promoted as \"The Nation's Greatest Playground on the Pacific Coast\" Luna Park was \"thronged\" after it opened in the summer of 1907. During its first Independence Day, Lewis MacEvoy and Angela May claimed to have sold to the crowds on this gated platform more than 4000 copies of their new song \"All Aboard for Luna Park.\" (Historical pix courtesy Oregon Historical Society)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/luna-park-entrances-then-mr21.jpg"},{"t":"3rd and Spring regrade","d":"2011-09-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-3rd-and-spring-regrade/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Looking south across Spring Street and into the pit along Third Avenue for its 1906-7 regrade.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/3-spring-regrade-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"the Pike Pier Fishing Fleet","d":"2011-09-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-pike-pier-fishing-fleet/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Throughout much of the first half of the 20th Century, the Pike Street Dock, here on the right, was home to the fishing fleet. If that is snow marking the roof of the Schwabacher Wharf, on the left, the fleet is here on a winter break.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/pike-street-fleet-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The First Presbyterians","d":"2011-10-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-first-presbyterians/","lat":47.6079,"lon":-122.3258,"c":"place_approx","x":"M.L. Oakes, Seattle's prolific \"real photo postcard artist,\" recorded this interior of Seattle's First Presbyterian Church most like when it was brand new, or nearly, in 1907. The church was located at Seventh Ave. and Spring Street, and there the congregation has stayed.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/1st-presby-interior-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Section Lines on Wallingford Hill","d":"2011-10-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-section-lines-on-wallingford-hill/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Looking through the main business intersection of what once called the Wallingford Hill District, but now is simply Wallingford. Trolley 702 looks west on 45th Street and across Meridian Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/45-meridian-w-trolley-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Centralia Depot","d":"2011-10-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-centralia-depot/","lat":46.7163,"lon":-122.954,"c":"place","x":"The Centralia Railroad Depot, recorded not long after its opening in 1912.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/centralia-depot-thenmr1.jpg"},{"t":"Rivoli Follies","d":"2011-10-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-rivoli-follies/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"Lawton Gowey's afternoon look south on the east side of First Avenue from Madison Street during the \"spring of love\" in 1967. All three structures – notably the Rivoli Theatre at Madison St. on the left and the Stevens Hotel at Marion – were then slated for destruction.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rivoli-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Go-Hing on King","d":"2011-10-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-go-hing-on-king/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"Some of the young men posing here on King Street with their backs to 7th Avenue may be members of the Chinese Students Club at the University of Washington. During its May 1921 coverage of the six-day Go-Hing carnival, The Seattle Times identified the club as \"the organization which is backing . . . the native celebration in Chinatown this week.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/king-st-go-hing-thenmr1.jpg"},{"t":"First Avenue South","d":"2011-11-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-first-avenue-south/","lat":47.61018,"lon":-122.34136,"c":"addr","x":"After the city's \"great fire\" of 1889 First Avenue south of King Street was extended far and wide into the tideflats. An exception to the city's post-fire \"brick rule\" the first structures here were made of wood, and so replaced by masonry early in the 20th Century.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/first-s-fm-king-thenmr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Tacoma Public Library","d":"2011-11-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-tacoma-public-library/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place","x":"Tacoma's Public Library, was the 85th Carnegie library built in the United States, but the first in Washington State. Here the tower of the Pierce County Court House backs the library on the right and the old wood frame Central School appears on the left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/tacoma-library-then1.jpg"},{"t":"\"New Land, North of the Columbia\"","d":"2011-11-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-new-land-north-of-the-columbia/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place_approx","x":"A page copies from one of pioneer historian Thomas Prosch's two albums of early Seattle scenes. Prosch's own captions add both directions and personal tone to his albums.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/prosch-lorraine-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Chapin Block","d":"2011-11-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-chapin-block/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The ornate Colonial Building, aka the Chapin Block, held the northeast corner of Second Avenue, on the left, and Columbia Street, on the right, from 1888 to 1906.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/colonial-bldg-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Peiser's Parade","d":"2011-12-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-peisers-parade/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Looking northeast across Second Avenue to an Independence Day float – most likely in 1887 or 1888. It is appointed with bunting and examples of the Lake Union Furniture company's work as well as demonstrations of the company's skilled carpenters at work.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/peiser-parade-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"\"Before Seattle Rocked\"","d":"2011-12-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-before-seattle-rocked/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.3127,"c":"place_approx","x":"Left to right, Alice Stuart, Bill Sheldon and Dallas Williams at the Pamir Folksingers cabaret on \"the Ave\" in 1962.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/before-seattle-rocked-then21.jpg"},{"t":"'Cyrene' not 'Latona'","d":"2011-12-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-cyrene-not-latona/","lat":47.63,"lon":-122.258,"c":"place","x":"The original Cyrene resting, most likely, somewhere on Lake Washington before it was enlarged in 1903.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/cyrene-sic-latonamr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"the Jackson Street Regrade","d":"2011-12-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-jackson-street-regrade/","lat":47.5985,"lon":-122.322,"c":"place","x":"Lowering the grade of Weller Street with eroding blasts of salt water was one of the early goals of the Jackson Street Regrade. Much the resulting mud was directed west to the tide flats, helping to raise and reclaim them for saleable real estate. The construction scaffolding for the Frye Hotel at 3rd and Yelser is seen on the left. Courtesy: John Cooper","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/jackson-regrade-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Genealogy","d":"2011-12-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-genealogy/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place_approx","x":"Genealogist Darlene Hamilton, on the left, no longer remembers what particular research tome she and her predecessor Carol Lind held together for this ca. 1971 portrait in the genealogy alcove of central library. The photographer was, most likely, Lind's friend Joseph W. Marshall.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/geneology-library-then21.jpg"},{"t":"the Bus(c)h Hotel","d":"2012-01-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-busch-hotel/","lat":47.5985,"lon":-122.323,"c":"place","x":"This well-marked block on the south side of Jackson Street includes the Bush Hotel, still a Chinatown landmark.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/bush-hotel-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"30 Years of Dorpat","d":"2012-01-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-30-years-of-dorpat/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"The tarnished recording of Sara and Henry Yesler's home in Pioneer Square is the oldest surviving photographic evidence of any part of Seattle. It is conventionally dated 1859, or seven years after the first settlers on the eastern shores of Elliott Bay moved there from Alki Point.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/yesler-home-1st-photo-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Coming Home to Riverside","d":"2012-01-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-coming-home-to-riverside/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place_approx","x":"Propping the game's head on the erect barrel of his rifle, Riverside resident John Edgar Vincent poses with his fall quarry, circa 1946.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/riverside-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Central Business District, ca.1872","d":"2012-01-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-central-business-district-1876/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The still forested First Hill, upper left, and Beacon Hill, center and right, draw the horizon above the still sparsely developed north end of Seattle's residential neighborhood in 1872-73. Second Avenue angles across the center of the subject, and also intersects there with Union Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/cbd-ca-1876-fm-d-hill-then-red-arrowsweb1.jpg"},{"t":"Fire Station No. 9","d":"2012-02-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-fire-station-no-9/","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place","x":"Seattle's Fire Station #9 in Fremont replaced a volunteer force in 1901 with this stately box. Built on the west side of Linden Ave. N. just south of N. 39th Street, the wood frame station was replaced by a new station in the early 1950s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/fremont-fire-station-23-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle Now and Then: Christian Scientists","d":"2012-02-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-and-then-christian-scientists/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Made of Bedford Limestone, the First Church of Christ Scientist at the southwest corner of 16th Avenue and E.Denny Way on Capitol Hill, took five years to complete.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/first-christian-scientist-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Governor Martin's Starvation Camp","d":"2012-02-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-governor-martins-starvation-camp/","lat":47.62,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place_approx","x":"Up for less than one week in the Spring of 1939, the jobless and hungry protest signed \"Gov. Martin's Starvation Camp No. 2\" was one of City Hall Park's many depression-time uses for public protests and mass meetings during the Great Depression.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/gov-martins-starvationcamp-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Jolly Roger on Lake City Way","d":"2012-02-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-jolly-roger-on-lake-city-way/","lat":47.718,"lon":-122.294,"c":"place","x":"Included in a box of Chinese Castle and Jolly Roger ephemera – menus, fliers, ledgers, and photographs – that collector Ron Edge uncovered were three photos of the roadhouse bedded in snow – three different snows. We chose \"the middle one\" from the 1940s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/jolly-roger-in-snow-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Snowbound on Second","d":"2012-03-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-snowbound-on-second/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"In 1916, the year of this \"big snow,\" the Bon Marche Department Store, on the right, was already 20 years at the southwest corner of Second Avenue and Pike Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/second-snow-then1.jpg"},{"t":"the Tacoma Hotel","d":"2012-03-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-tacoma-hotel/","lat":47.647,"lon":-122.452,"c":"place","x":"Designed by the famous New York architect Stanford White, the Tacoma Hotel opened in 1884 one year after the transcontinental Northern Pacific Railroad first reached Tacoma, its Puget Sound terminus. The Mason Building on the right at the southeast corner of S. 10th St. and A St. was built in 1887 with its own namesake hotel.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/tacoma-hotel-1891-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Tacoma Interurban at Occidental","d":"2012-03-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-tacoma-interurban-at-occidental/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"With his or her back to the Elegant Seattle Hotel an unnamed photographer looks south across Yesler Way to the busy terminus of the Seattle Tacoma Interurban Railway. (Pix courtesy of Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/tacoma-interurban-on-occidental-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Row Houses on 5th","d":"2012-03-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-row-houses-on-5th/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place","x":"With his or her back to the then still future site of the Seattle Public Library, an unnamed photographer looks south on 5th Avenue thru its intersection with Madison Street. The piles of dirt and temporary small construction in the street may have something to do with building the Madison Street cable railway, which begin giving service in the summer of 1890.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/row-houses-5th-madison-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"A Golden Rule for April Fools","d":"2012-04-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-a-golden-rule-for-april-fools/","lat":47.60357,"lon":-122.33225,"c":"addr","x":"It was surely a bright idea to use Golden Rule, the name for the central moral maxim of humankind \"Do unto others as you would have them do unto you.\" as also the banner for one's emporium of often bargain-priced housewares.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/golden-rule-bazaar-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"-Seattle Now & Then: The Nine Millionth Visitor","d":"2012-04-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-nine-millionth-visitor/","lat":47.5301,"lon":-122.0326,"c":"place_approx","x":"With her sister Nancy and her dad Harold standing behind her and her mom Laura, here on the left, Paula Dahl (Jones) has just learned that she alone is Century 21's \"goal marker,\" the world fair's 9 millionth visitor. She recalls, \"Once I realized I hadn't done anything wrong I started to feel pretty excited.\" (Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/paula-dahl-jones-9-millionth-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Shared Walls","d":"2012-04-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-shared-walls/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Construction work begins on the top three floors of the Hermosa Apartments, on the left, at the northeast corner of 4th Avenue and Cedar Street. The view looks over Denny Way to Tilikum Place and west on Cedar Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/hermosa-apts-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Beaumont Apartments","d":"2012-04-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-beaumont-apartments-2/","lat":47.61427,"lon":-122.32543,"c":"addr","x":"The Beaumont, upper-left at 1512 Summit Ave. in 1920, was one of hundreds of apartment houses built on First and Capitol Hills in the early 20th Century. Typical of many were two bays that like these on the Beaumont climbed to the roof. The Beaumont's bays are also given ornamental crowns beyond the roof. Between the bays and framed at the center, open balconies lead to the hallways on the apartme","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/beaumont-apts-1512-summit-then-mr11.jpg"},{"t":"9th & University","d":"2012-05-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-9th-university/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"On the hot and quiet Sunday afternoon of June 4, 1961 Frank Shaw stepped onto the short pedestrian bridge that once extended from the Normandie Apartments, here far right, over the lower intersection of 9th and University. The intersection was divided in half - a high part and a low part - because this was one of the very few precipitous parts of First Hill. (Historical photo by Frank Shaw)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/9th-university-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Emma Haywood","d":"2012-05-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-emma-haywood/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"One hundred and seventy-seven feet long, and twenty-nine feet wide, the Emma Hayward had a hold seven feet deep. It rests here on the Seattle Waterfront ca. 1885 at the foot of Main Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/emma-hayward-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Mrs. Anderson's Eccentric Ride","d":"2012-05-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-mrs-andersons-eccentric-ride/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Mason County \"lumberpersons\" Agnes and Alfred Anderson built this big home at the southeast corner of Minor Avenue and Columbia Street, appropriately in the First Hill neighborhood of mansions. Here's Agnes poses in her carriage, before taking her daily ride.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/mrs.-anderson-then-mr-500x351.jpg"},{"t":"The Wilkes Theatre","d":"2012-05-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-wilkes-theatre/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place","x":"Photographed in 1921 by the Webster and Stevens Studio for a Seattle Times report on the Wilkes Theatre's imminent change from stage shows to motion pictures.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/wilkes-theatre-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Westlake and Thomas","d":"2012-06-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"In January of 1902, the probable year for this cityscape on Westlake, City Council decided to connect this oldest part of Westlake between Lake Union and Denny Way with the central business district by extending it directly through and upsetting the city grid as far south as 4th and Pike. A Seattle Times clipping from the time and describing this decision is printed below.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/westlake-at-thomas-1902-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Suburbia near Dearborn","d":"2012-06-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-suburbia-on-dearborn/","lat":47.578,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place_approx","x":"This right half of a Carleton Watkins' Stereopticon card titled \"suburban residence, Seattle W.T.\" includes several clues for its location.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/suburban-home-dearborn-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Issaquah Coal Strike","d":"2012-06-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-issaquah-coal-strike/","lat":47.5301,"lon":-122.0326,"c":"place","x":"A company of state militia pose on what is now Issaquah's E. Sunset Way. The Bellevue Hotel is in the background of what was then still called Gilman after Daniel Gilman, one of the promoters who opened King County's resource-rich hinterlands to industrial development in the late 1880s with the construction of the Seattle Lake Shore and Eastern Railroad. Courtesy, Issaquah Historical Museum.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/issaquah-coal-strike-guardsthen-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Yesler's Sheds","d":"2012-06-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-yeslers-sheds/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"After Seattle's Great Fire of June 6, 1889, temporary lodgings for burned-out businesses were hastily assembled, some above the ashes and others, like these sheds facing Third Avenue south of James Street, nearby.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/post-89-fire-yesler-front-yard-then-lr1.jpg"},{"t":"Buzby's Waterfront Mill","d":"2012-07-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-buzbys-waterfront-mill/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Through the late 1870s the Starr Mill at the waterfront foot of Seneca Street was the primary provider of flour and feed to locals. The unnamed photographer's back is to a log seawall (1876) that held Front Street (First Avenue) above the waterfront. The mill was supported on some combination of rubble and pilings. (Photo courtesy of Ron Edge)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/busby-mill-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"KRAB – Listener Supported Free-form Radio","d":"2012-07-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-krab-listener-supported-free-form-radio/","lat":47.6189,"lon":-122.313,"c":"place","x":"(click to enlarge photos) NOTE PLEASE: You may wish to check the comments (at the very bottom) for the growing list of names and ruminations connected with this picture. Some others were sent to me directly, and I have encouraged those correspondents to also return to the blog and post them here. I hope that is easy to do. THEN: I have held this subject back for probably twenty years waiting for K","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/krab-radio-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle Center Corral","d":"2012-07-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-seattle-center-corral/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"Pioneer photographer Theodore Peiser's record of the U.S. Army corral in the future Seattle Center dates from the summer of 1900. The tower of the old Mercer School at Valley Street and 4th Avenue can be found above the hat of the cowboy nearest the scene's center. (Photo courtesy University of Washington Libraries, Special Collections.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/corral-seattle-center-1900-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"MOHAI's Seattle Fire Mural","d":"2012-07-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-mohais-seattle-fire-mural/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"\"Scientific muralist\" Ruddy Zallinger works on his depiction of the Great Seattle Fire of June 6, 1889 from a prospect that looks east on Yesler Way (Mill Street then) to its old pre-fire intersection with First Avenue (Front Street then).","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/1889-fire-mural-at-mohai-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Phinney Ridge Ferris Wheel","d":"2012-07-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-phinney-ridge-ferris-wheel/","lat":47.67,"lon":-122.355,"c":"place","x":"Between 1919 and 1934 the northwest corner of Phinney Avenue and N.E. 55th Street was home to an amusement center that was a city-wide attraction.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/phinney-ferris-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Wilhelmina/Winona Apartments","d":"2012-08-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-wilhelminawinona-apartments/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"Built in about 1907, the Wilhelmina if not the first apartment house on Queen Anne Hill was surely one of the earliest.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/the-wilhelmina-apt-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Dominion Monarch","d":"2012-08-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/seattle-now-and-then/seattle-now-then-the-dominion-monarch/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3375,"c":"place","x":"The ocean liner Dominion Monarch arrived in Seattle from Southampton, England on May 29, 1962 to a noisy Worlds' Fair public relations greeting while it was carefully slipped between pilings especially driven beside Pier 50, where it was moored as a \"boatel\" for the duration of its service thru the duration of Century 21. It was a brief reprieve for following the fair the liner sailed for Japan wh","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/dominion-monarch-june-20-1962-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Second Hill from First Hill","d":"2012-08-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/08/18/seattle-now-then-second-hill-from-first-hill/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Eight blocks up Second Hill the twin towers of Immaculate Conception Parish at 18th Avenue and E. Marion Street own the horizon in 1905 and still do.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/2nd-hill-fm-seattle-university-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Cascade Hotel Spectacle","d":"2012-08-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/08/25/seattle-now-then-cascade-hotel-spectacle/","lat":47.623,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"After 40 years at the busy center of Granite Falls in Snohomish County, the Cascade Hotel was cut down by fire in1933 but not razed.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/cascade-hotel-spectacle-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Palace Hip Theatre","d":"2012-09-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/09/08/seattle-now-then-the-palace-hip-theatre/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Photographed on April 30th, 1921, the Palace Hip at the southeast corner of Spring Street and Second Avenue mostly prospered until it closed in the Spring of 1929, still months before the crashing start of the Great Depression. The Seattle Times explained, \"The heyday of vaudeville is over and with it into history fades one of its former strongholds.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/palace-hip-theater-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Mrs. Anderson, Co-eds, and Mea Culpa","d":"2012-09-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/09/15/seattle-now-then-mrs-anderson-co-eds-and-mea-culpa/","lat":47.6097,"lon":-122.3192,"c":"place","x":"With their windows open, joyful Seattle University co-eds greet Spring and a Seattle Times photographer from their First Hill mansion-dormitory in April 1959. (Picture courtesy, Lois Crow)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/anderson-mchugh-hall-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Schmitz Park Arch","d":"2012-09-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/09/22/seattle-now-then-the-schmitz-park-arch/","lat":47.568,"lon":-122.403,"c":"place","x":"The Schmitz Park arch straddled 59th Avenue Southwest facing Alki Beach from 1913 to 1953.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/schmitz-park-arch-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Federal Courthouse","d":"2012-09-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/09/29/seattle-now-then-the-federal-courthouse/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place","x":"Show here in late 1939, across the intersection of Spring Street and 5th Avenue, the building site chosen for the Federal Courthouse, was surrounded for the most part by hotels, apartments, schools, churches, and, to the west across 5th Avenue, the lush landscape of the Carnegie-built Seattle Public Library, here lower-right.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/1.-future-courthouse-site-1937-web-500x322.jpg"},{"t":"Fair and Festival – Belgian Waffles","d":"2012-10-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/10/13/seattle-now-then-fair-and-festival-belgian-waffles/","lat":47.6212,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"Somewhat like an oversized doll-house the faux Flemish facades of the Belgian Waffle confectionary were not examples of the \"forward thrust\" normally expected of Century 21's architecture. Both views look east on Republican Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/belgian-waffle-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Dennys' Green Acres","d":"2012-10-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/10/21/seattle-now-then-the-dennys-green-acres/","lat":47.6212,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"For Jean and I it is a delightful irony that The Century 21 Master Plan for Seattle Center describes razing the High School Stadium part of the Center for a green \"open space\" like - and also on! - these grassy blocks that pioneer's David and Louise Denny long withheld from development.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/dennys-potlatch-field-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Arabian Theatre","d":"2012-10-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/10/27/seattle-now-then-the-arabian-theatre/","lat":47.68416,"lon":-122.34433,"c":"addr","x":"The Arabian Theatre opened in 1925 with the Daniel Bagley Primary School two blocks north (the towers are showing, left of center) and its thruway, Aurora Ave., preparing for four decades of service to the Pacific Coast Highway. With its exotic tower and stain glass the theatre was designed to lure motorists and shoppers on would develop into an almost endless strip of small businesses.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/arabian-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Hollywood Tavern","d":"2012-11-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/11/03/seattle-now-then-the-hollywood-tavern-on-university/","lat":47.6107,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place_approx","x":"For most of the last century this quaint Inn nestled mid-block on the north side of University Street between Second and Third Avenues.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/hollywood-tavern-univ-st-1938mr-copy1.jpg"},{"t":"Motorcycles and Art on Third Avenue South","d":"2012-11-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/11/11/seattle-now-then-motorcycles-and-art-on-third-avenue/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Third from the right, Grace Loudon McAdams steadies her brother Max's motorcycle for his recording of this fashionably snug line-up. Grace and her friends pose on a Third Avenue sidewalk about one-half block south of Washington Street, ca.1919.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/max-loudons-girls-on-3rd-s.-w-motorcycle-then-mr--500x335.jpg"},{"t":"The Ishii Family Farm","d":"2012-11-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/11/18/seattle-now-then-the-ishii-family-farm/","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"The ca. 1935 view looks northwest towards West Seattle from the Ishii family farm. The west pier of the 14th Ave S. bascule bridge over the Duwamish Waterway to South Park can be found between what Nancy Ishii identifies as the farm house topped by a giant cedar stump, center, and the barn, far left. Posing, R-L, are Nancy's grandfather Tadaichi Ishii, her aunts, Sally (Ishii) Tsuboi and Michi (Is","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/ishii-family-farm-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Billboards on Third Avenue","d":"2012-11-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/11/24/seattle-now-then-billboards-on-third-avenue/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Foster and Kleiser, the outdoor advertising monopoly, in 920 claimed that it did more than 90 percent of billboards in the Northwest. Here two years earlier, at the northeast corner of Seneca St. and Third Avenue, it poses some of its most ornate work like posh picture frames on a fireplace mantle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/3rd-ne-cor-seneca-1918-billboards-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Central Seattle Service Station","d":"2012-12-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/12/01/seattle-now-then-the-central-seattle-service-station/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place_approx","x":"Both this service station on 6th Avenue and the nearly ancient tenement apartments beside it and facing Columbia Street, survived into the late 1950s, the years of planning for the Seattle Freeway that replace both.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/standard-station-on-6th-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Atlas Theatre","d":"2012-12-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/12/08/seattle-now-then-the-atlas-theatre/","lat":47.5985,"lon":-122.323,"c":"place","x":"This subject of a drum major leading the funeral parade for Dong On Long through Seattle's Chinatown was photographed by The Seattle Times but not used in its May 12, 1941 report on the parade. We revive it now. (Ron Edge)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/atlas-theatre-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Town Hall (+ Another Rogue's Christmas)","d":"2012-12-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/12/15/seattle-now-then-town-hall-another-rogues-christmas/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"During the Spring or Summer of 1923, an unnamed photographer, visited Virginia Mason Hospital at the northwest corner of Terry Avenue and Spring Street to record this panorama of the newest landmarks in the Central Business District above also a few from First Hill, including the Fourth Church Christ Scientist, far left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/town-hall-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Ballard's Bascule Bridge","d":"2012-12-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/12/22/seattle-now-then-ballards-bascule-bridge/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"Ballard's Railroad Depot and the Great Northern Railroad's landmark lift bridge just west of the ship canal's Chittenden Locks.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/ballard-rr-station-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Rainier Club & the Burnett Home","d":"2012-12-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2012/12/29/seattle-now-then-the-rainier-club-the-burnett-home/","lat":47.6055,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place","x":"The 53-year-old Burnett home at the northeast corner of 4th Ave. and Columbia Street was completed nearly forty years before the Rainier Club was built at the north end of the block in 1904. In between them, and showing far left, the Burnett's built a small apartment house. The family named it for itself, the Burnett Flats.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/4-columbia-necor-rainier-club-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Frank Shaw's Big Neighbor","d":"2013-01-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/01/05/seattle-now-then-frank-shaws-big-neighbor/","lat":47.6205,"lon":-122.3493,"c":"place","x":"Work on the Washington State Coliseum began early in 1960. For Frank Shaw it wasn't until the early summer of '61 that the Space Needle suddenly emerged from the Coliseum's roof line and kept on ascending. From his apartment windows Shaw photographed the view of the superimposed and still growing landmarks on September 16, 1961","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/century-21-construct-9-16-61-shaw-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Alley to James Street","d":"2013-01-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/01/13/23791/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place","x":"Looking north down the Alley between Jefferson and James Street, in the First Hill block also bordered by Sixth and Seventh Avenues.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/x-james-street-alley-then-mr11.jpg"},{"t":"Georgetown Firemen on Pike","d":"2013-01-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/01/19/seattle-now-then-georgetown-firemen-on-pike/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Outside of the \"fire district\" where building in brick and stone was required following Seattle's \"Great Fire\" of 1889, the rest of the central city was still built mostly of wood, often with lodgings above and retail at the sidewalk, like here at 7th Ave. and Pike Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/pike-7th-parading-firemen-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Pachyderms in Pioneer Square","d":"2013-01-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/01/26/seattle-now-then-pachyderms-in-pioneer-square/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place","x":"Thanks to Seattle Public Library's \"Seattle Room\" librarian Jeannette Voiland for encouraging me to treat this Pioneer Square parade as part of the 1912 Golden Potlatch Parade. I'm convinced.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/elephant-1st-wash-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"First and Pike – Nov. 6th 1953, 2:25 PM","d":"2013-02-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/02/01/seattle-now-then-first-and-pike-nov-6th-1953-225-pm/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Concerned more with the street clock than all else between the bundled pedestrians on the left and the taxi on the right, this satisfying composition of Pike Street east from First Avenue was photographed with an ulterior motive.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/pike-st-lk-e-to-2nd-n-side-nov-6-1953-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"A B50 crash near Airport Way","d":"2013-02-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/02/09/seattle-now-then-a-b50-crash-near-airport-way/","lat":47.6168,"lon":-122.336,"c":"place_approx","x":"Both this \"then\" and Jean's \"now\" were photographed looking southeast from Airport Way through South Stevens Street. The great brick pile of the Rainier Brewery is just out of frame to the right (south) in both views.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/beacon-hill-crash-3100-airport-way-aug.-19-1951-mr-1-500x616.jpg"},{"t":"The Northern Life (aka Seattle) Tower","d":"2013-02-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/02/16/seattle-now-then-the-northern-life-aka-seattle-tower/","lat":47.6072,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place_approx","x":"In the mere nine months between the laying of its cornerstone on June 6, 1928 to the April 5, 1929 celebration of its completion, architect A.H Albertson's Art Deco Northern Life Tower at the southeast corner of Third Ave. and University Street became what many locals consider still the finest structure in Seattle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/1-the-old-order-changeth-grab-web1.jpg"},{"t":"The American Hotel on Westlake","d":"2013-02-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/02/23/seattle-now-then-the-american-hotel-on-westlake/","lat":47.62,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Back to back, the American Hotel on the left, and the first five floors of the Northern Bank and Trust building, fill the then new pie-shaped half-block east of Westlake between Pike and Pine Streets. A likely date is ca. 1908.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/american-hotel-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The New Railroad Avenue","d":"2013-03-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/03/02/seattle-now-then-the-new-railroad-avenue/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"Snapped from the Fire Station #5 tower in late 1901 (or early 1902) it nicely displays the then new Northern Pacific Piers facing a widened Railroad Ave. (Alaskan Way) north of Madison Street. In two years more and the trestle for wagons and rail spurs would be completed across the watery gap in the foreground.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/pier-3-changes-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Orpheum Descending","d":"2013-03-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/03/09/seattle-now-then-orpheum-descending/","lat":47.62,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"At 5th and Westlake, Seattle's last of three Orpheum Theatres opened in 1927 and served up vaudeville, concerts and movies from its corner for 40 years. It has been observed that had the theatre made it for a half-century, the local forces of preservation would have never allowed its destruction. And the difficulties encountered wrecking it, suggested that this Orpheum could have stood 400 years.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/orpheum-proscenium-destruction-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Signal Station on Aurora","d":"2013-03-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/03/16/seattle-now-then-signal-station-on-aurora/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place_approx","x":"Five blocks south of what was then still city limits along 85th Street, the landmark Signal Station at 80th & Aurora, with its own comely tower, added class to Seattle's contribution to the Pacific Coast Highway. The modern ribbon of concrete was poured to both speed and service traffic between Mexico and Canada.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/cunningham-signal-80-aurora-37-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Gables Apartments on Capitol Hill","d":"2013-03-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/03/23/seattle-now-then-the-gables-apartments-on-capitol-hill/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Built of local Denny-Renton Brick in 1911, the Gables was one of the largest apartment houses then on Capitol Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/gables-apts-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Upheaval on Spring Street","d":"2013-03-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/03/30/seattle-now-then-upheaval-on-spring-street/","lat":47.6066,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Looking east up Spring Street from 5th Ave. during its ca. 1909 regrade.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/spring-st-regrade-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle's First Rep","d":"2013-04-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/04/06/seattle-now-then-3/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.368,"c":"place_approx","x":"Some of the 1946 cast for Calico Cargo face-off at the Seattle Repertory Playhouse on University Way at N.E. 41st Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/calico-cargo-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"2nd and University","d":"2013-04-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/04/13/seattle-now-then-2nd-and-university/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"For reasons not revealed, in the late winter of 1901 a photographer turned her or his camera on the soon to be cleared clutter at the northeast corner of Second Avenue and University Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/second-university-necor-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle (aka Broadway) High School","d":"2013-04-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/04/20/seattle-now-then-seattle-aka-broadway-high-school/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Aiming north into Capitol Hill from the north end of First Hill, an as yet anonymous photographer made a rare record of the then new Seattle High School's south façade.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/seattle-hight-school-lk-no.-thru-pike-on-harvard-mr-then-500x308.jpg"},{"t":"Hole off of Holgate","d":"2013-04-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/04/27/seattle-now-then-hole-off-of-holgate/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"The work of filling the tidelands south of King Street began in 1853 with the chips from Yesler's sawmill. Here in the neighborhood of 9th Ave. S. (Airport Way) and Holgate Street, the tideland reclaiming and street regrading continue 70 years later in 1923.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/holgate-lk-e-to-9th-1922-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Echo Lake Landmark","d":"2013-05-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/05/04/seattle-now-then-echo-lake-landmark/","lat":47.7706,"lon":-122.34587,"c":"addr","x":"Three Echo Lake proprietors are signed in this ca. 1938 tax photo. On the right is Scotty's hanging invitation to his Paradise. Eddie Erickson's sign to his Echo Lake Camp appears, in part, far left. Between them is Aurora's enduring landmark, Melby's Echo Lake Tavern.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/echo-lake-tavern-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Lutherans on the Move","d":"2013-05-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/05/11/seattle-now-then-lutherans-on-the-move/","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1888-89 at the northeast corner of Fourth Avenue and Pine Street, the then named Norwegian-Danish Evangelical Lutheran Church marked the southeast corner of Denny Hill. Eventually the lower land to the east of the church (here behind it) would be filled, in part, with hill dirt scraped and eroded from North Seattle lots to the north and west of this corner.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/norwegian-danish-lutheran-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Queen Anne Pioneers","d":"2013-05-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/05/18/seattle-now-then-queen-anne-pioneers/","lat":47.61593,"lon":-122.3388,"c":"addr","x":"This row of homes, right to left, from 2104 to 2110 7th Ave. West were built in 1905-6, and so they are, by some calibrations, antiques. They are well cared for Queen Anne Hill pioneers. Public School teacher Lou R. Key lived for time at 2104 7th Ave. West, the second house from the right, if I have figured it correctly. For notes on these homes – and on Ms. Key too – see the bottom of this featur","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/crockett-7-w.-row-then-mr-500x325.jpg"},{"t":"The Four Winds","d":"2013-05-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/05/24/seattle-now-then-the-four-winds/","lat":47.6205,"lon":-122.3493,"c":"place","x":"Photographed in the late 1950s, the floating restaurant's huge on deck hooligan got no competition as yet from the Space Needle (1962) in breaking the horizon.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/four-winds-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Graystone on First Hill","d":"2013-06-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/06/01/seattle-now-then-the-graystone-on-first-hill/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Covered with cut stone the row house facing Marion Street on First Hill was intended to begin a local trend for elegant townhouse construction until such plans and much else were interrupted by the financial Panic of 1893.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/graystone-then1.jpg"},{"t":"A Fremont Trolley Derailed","d":"2013-06-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/06/07/seattle-now-then-a-fremont-trolley-derailed/","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place","x":"The rear end of the derailed trolley on N. 35th Street appears right-of-center a few feet east of Albion Place N. and the curved track from which the unrestrained car jumped on the morning of August 21, 1903.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/fremont-trolley-derail-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Beacon Hill Traffic","d":"2013-06-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/06/15/seattle-now-then-beacon-hill-traffic/","lat":47.578,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place","x":"A speeding coupe convertible heads north on Beacon Hill's 15th Ave. S. in 1937","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/beacon-hill-traffic-then1.jpg"},{"t":"A Night in Old Alexandria","d":"2013-06-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/06/21/seattle-now-then-a-night-in-old-alexandria/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place_approx","x":"Revelers pose on the Masonic Temple stage for \"A Night in Old Alexandria,\" the Seattle Fine Art Societies annual costume ball for 1921. (Pic courtesy of Arthur \"Link\" Lingenbrink)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a-night-in-old-alexandria-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Latona Bridge","d":"2013-06-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/06/29/seattle-now-then-the-latona-bridge/","lat":47.658,"lon":-122.404,"c":"place","x":"The Latona Bridge was constructed in 1891 along the future line of the Lake Washington Ship Canal Bridge. The photo was taken from the Seattle Lake Shore and Eastern Railway right-of-way, now the Burke Gilman Recreation Trail. The Northlake Apartment/Hotel on the right survived and struggled into the 1960s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/latona-bridge-then11.jpg"},{"t":"Dennys on Boren","d":"2013-07-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/07/06/seattle-now-then-dennys-on-boren/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"Many members of the Arthur and Mary Denny Family moved to homes on Boren Avenue, which were set back to back first on Seneca Street and then here at 1220 Boren, on University Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/boren-university-denny-ainsworth-homes-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Mukai Farm Matters","d":"2013-07-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/07/13/seattle-now-then-the-mukai-farm-matters/","lat":47.44,"lon":-122.476,"c":"place","x":"Twenty years ago the Mukai Farm and Garden on Vashon Island was designated a King County Landmark.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/mukai-then-mr2.jpg"},{"t":"The Old Colony Apartments","d":"2013-07-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/07/20/seattle-now-then-the-old-colony-apartments/","lat":47.60659,"lon":-122.32273,"c":"addr","x":"First Hill's distinguished Old Colony Apartments at 615 Boren Avenue, 1910.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/old-colony-615-boren-ave-then-mr.-500x330.jpg"},{"t":"North Side Realty","d":"2013-07-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/07/27/seattle-now-then-north-side-realty/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place_approx","x":"Chalk-written real estate notices to the sides of Seattle's Aurora Speedway in 1937 prelude by several decades the profession's book and computer listings and the expectation of some that an agent will now be driving a Mercedes.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/north-side-realty-mr3-then-tax1.jpg"},{"t":"Stan Sayres on Broadway","d":"2013-08-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/08/03/seattle-now-then-stan-sayres-on-broadway/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.321,"c":"place","x":"The front end damage to the white Shepard Ambulance on the right is mostly hidden behind the black silhouette of either officer Murphy or Lindberg, both of whom answered the call of this morning crash on Feb. 18, 1955.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/stan-sayers-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Hizzoner's Long Home Run","d":"2013-08-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/08/10/seattle-now-then-hizzoners-long-home-run/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place"},{"t":"Sweet Fun at Bitter Lake","d":"2013-08-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/08/17/seattle-now-then-sweet-fun-at-bitter-lake/","lat":47.725,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"Far-left, Playland's Acroplane, a carny flight-simulator, stands admired by future pilots in 1932. Behind them sprawls the amusement park's fated Fun House.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/playland-funhouse-mr-then21.jpg"},{"t":"Lake Ballinger","d":"2013-08-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/08/24/seattle-now-then-lake-ballinger/","lat":47.778,"lon":-122.3127,"c":"place","x":"Julia and Richard Ballinger owned a \"gas-powered\" rowboat to reach their summer home on their namesake Lake Ballinger. This 1911 view looks east from near the tracks of the Seattle-Everett Interurban.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lake-ballinger-dtl-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"West Seattle School","d":"2013-08-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/08/31/seattle-now-then-west-seattle-school/","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1893, West Seattle School kept teaching until ruined by the region's 1949 earthquake.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/west-seattle-school-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Fourth and Olive","d":"2013-09-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/09/07/seattle-now-then-fourth-and-olive/","lat":47.616,"lon":-122.3345,"c":"cross","x":"While visiting Seattle for some promoting, silent film star Wallace Reid shares the sidewalk at 4th and Olive with a borrowed Stutz Bearcat.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/stutz-bearcat-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Submarine Launch","d":"2013-09-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/09/14/seattle-now-then-submarine-launch/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place_approx","x":"The new sub H-3 takes her inaugural baptism at the Seattle Construction and Dry Dock Company's ways on Independence Day, 1913.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/h-3-submarine-launch-july-4-1913-mr-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Rowe's Row at 1st and Bell","d":"2013-09-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/09/20/seattle-now-then-rowes-row-at-1st-and-bell/","lat":47.6131,"lon":-122.338,"c":"cross","x":"Louis Rowe's row of storefronts at the southwest corner of First Ave. (then still named Front Street) and Bell Street appear in both the 1884 Sanborn real estate map and the city's 1884 birdseye sketch. Most likely this view dates from 1888-89.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/first-bell-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Secular Conversions at Third & Pine","d":"2013-09-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/09/28/seattle-now-then-secular-conversions-at-third-pine/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Sometime between early December 1906 and mid-February 1907 an unnamed photographer with her or his back about two lots north of Pike Street recorded landmarks on the east side of Third Avenue including, in part, the Washington Bar stables, on the right; the Union Stables at the center, a church converted for theatre at Pine Street, and north of Pine up a snow-dusted Denny Hill, the Washington Hote","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/union-stables-on-3rd-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Washington State Building of the AYPE","d":"2013-10-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/10/05/seattle-now-then-the-washington-state-building-of-the-aype/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"We suspect that this quiet exposure of the Washington State Building was photographed before the gates of the 1909 Alaska Yukon Pacific Exposition were first opened, and certainly before a bandstand gazebo was built in the grassy circle between it and the Forestry Building.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/wash-state-bldg-then-mr.-500x285.jpg"},{"t":"First Shovel at Fifth and Battery","d":"2013-10-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/10/12/seattle-now-then-first-shovel-at-fifth-and-battery/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"Before this the first shovel of the last of Denny Hill was ceremonially dropped to the conveyor belt at Battery Street, an \"initial bite of 30,000 cubic yards of material\" was carved from the cliff along the east side of 5th Avenue to make room for both the steam shovel and several moveable belts that extended like fingers across the hill. It was here that they met the elevated and fixed last leg ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/first-shovel-5th-battery-conveyor-5-11-29-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"AYP's Forestry Building","d":"2013-10-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/10/19/seattle-now-then-ayps-forestry-building/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"An estimated 50 percent of the materials used in the old Husky Union Building were recycled into its recent remodel. The new HUB seems to reach for the roof like its long-ago predecessor, the AYP's landmark Forestry building.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/ayp-forestry-building-then1.jpg"},{"t":"85th and Palatine","d":"2013-10-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/10/26/seattle-now-then-85th-and-palatine/","lat":47.689,"lon":-122.355,"c":"place","x":"The two motorcars parked irregularly in the foreground at the northeast corner of Palatine Ave. and N. 85th Street, are – I think – both Model-T Fords. Behind them the nearly completed Morrow Block reaches second floor apartments. Beyond the Fords are more Fords and examples of Greenwood commerce in 1925.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/85th-palatine-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Anthony Family Bindery","d":"2013-11-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/11/02/seattle-now-then-the-anthony-family-bindery/","lat":47.61187,"lon":-122.3335,"c":"addr","x":"Built in the mid-1880s at 1522 7th Avenue, the Anthony family home was part of a building boom developing this north end neighborhood then into a community of clapboards. Here 70 years later it is the lone survivor.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/fs-anthony-bindery-1522-7th-then1.jpg"},{"t":"First Hill by any other name…is just as steep","d":"2013-11-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/11/09/seattle-now-then-first-hill-by-any-other-name-is-just-as-steep/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place","x":"On his visit to the Smith Tower around 1960, Wade Stevenson recorded the western slope of First Hill showing Harborview Hospital and part of Yesler Terrace at the top between 7th and 9th Avenue but still little development in the two blocks between 7th and 5th Avenues. Soon the Seattle Freeway would create a concrete ditch between 7th and 6th (the curving Avenue that runs left-to-right through the","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/goat-hill-then1.jpg"},{"t":"The Ranke Home","d":"2013-11-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/11/16/seattle-now-then-the-ranke-home/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place","x":"We are not told but perhaps it is Dora and Otto Ranke and their four children posing with their home at 5th and Pike for the pioneer photographer Theo. E. Peiser ca. 1884. In the haze behind them looms Denny Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/ranke-home-on-pike-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Huck Finn in SODO","d":"2013-11-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/11/23/seattle-now-then-huck-finn-in-sodo/","lat":47.581,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Part of the pond that here in 1946 filled much of the long block between Massachusetts and Holgate Streets and 8th Avenue S. and Airport Way.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/tideflats-pond-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"'Lost Seattle'","d":"2013-11-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/11/30/seattle-now-then-lost-seattle/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"Between the now lost tower of the Pioneer Building, seen in part far left, and the Seattle Electric Steam Plant tower on the right, are arranged on First and Railroad Avenues the elaborate buzz of business beside and near Seattle's Pioneer Square ca. 1904.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/alaska-bldg-roof-view-to-west-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Amelia Apartments at 17th and Yesler","d":"2013-12-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/12/07/seattle-now-then-4/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Yesler Way's corner with 17th Avenue is about three blocks west and 30 feet short of Yesler Way's summit on Second Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/17th-yesler-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Union Bay Village","d":"2013-12-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/12/14/seattle-now-then-union-bay-village/","lat":47.657,"lon":-122.295,"c":"place","x":"On March 25, 1946, or near it, Wide World Photos recorded here what they titled \"University Vet Housing.\" It would soon be named the Union Bay Village and house the families of returning veterans. The first 45 bungalows shown here rented for from $35 to $45 dollars a month. It would increase to a \"teeming conglomerate of 500 rental units.\" With housing for both married students and faculty. The vi","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/union-bay-village-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Dorms near Frosh Pond","d":"2013-12-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/12/21/seattle-now-then-dorms-near-frosh-pond/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"The Gothic University of Washington Campus in 1946 beginning a seven-year crowding with prefabricated dormitories beside Frosh Pond. In the immediate background [on the right] is Guggenheim Hall.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/frosh-pond-housing-1946-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"Fairgrounds at Madison Park","d":"2013-12-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2013/12/29/seattle-now-then-fairgrounds-at-madison-park/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.278,"c":"place","x":"Looking southeast over the open acres of the Western Washington Fair Grounds following the matinee performance of Cheyenne Bill's Wild West Show during the summer of 1909.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/wast-wash-fair-grounds-then1.jpg"},{"t":"Amundsen's 'Maud'","d":"2014-01-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/01/05/seattle-now-then-amundsens-maud/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place_approx","x":"Tied momentarily to the end of the Union Oil Co dock off Bay Street, Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen's ship Maud prepares to cast-off for the Arctic Ocean on June 3, 1922.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/amundsens-maud-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"The Zindorf Apartments","d":"2014-01-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/01/11/seattle-now-then-the-zindorf-apartments/","lat":47.60552,"lon":-122.32765,"c":"addr","x":"A close \"read\" of this concrete pile at 714 7th Ave. will reveal many lines of tiles decorating its gray facades.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/zindorf-apts.-714-7th-ave.-mf-500x627.jpg"},{"t":"The First Fire Department HQ","d":"2014-01-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/01/19/seattle-now-then-the-first-fire-department-hq/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place_approx","x":"Constructed in 1890 as the Seattle Fire Department's first headquarters, these substantial four floors (counting the daylight basement) survived until replaced by Interstate Five in the 1960s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/1.-fs-fire-dept-headquarters-then-web-500x373.jpg"},{"t":"Fire Station No. 5","d":"2014-01-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/01/25/seattle-now-then-fire-station-no-5/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"Frank Shaw's late winter composition of waterfront landmarks at the foot of Madison Street in 1963.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/fs-fire-station-no-5-then-mr1.jpg"},{"t":"First Avenue South, 1961","d":"2014-02-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/02/04/seattle-now-then-first-avenue-south-1961/","lat":47.61071,"lon":-122.34215,"c":"addr","x":"Frank Shaw's pre-preservation visit to First Avenue South on February 26, 1961. He looks north from Main Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/fs-first-south-lk-no-fm-main-st-feb2661-web.jpg"},{"t":"Roosevelt Way, 1946","d":"2014-02-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/02/08/seattle-now-then-roosevelt-way-1946/","lat":47.677,"lon":-122.317,"c":"place","x":"Roosevelt Way bustling after the war. This subject first appeared in The Seattle Times on July 7, 1946.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/64th-roosevelt-1946-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Lady Rainier","d":"2014-02-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/02/15/seattle-now-then-lady-rainier/","lat":47.6168,"lon":-122.336,"c":"place_approx","x":"Sometime before her first move from this brewery courtyard in 1912, Lady Rainier was moved by a freeze to these sensational effects. She did not turn her fountain off.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/lady-rainier-then-mr2.jpg"},{"t":"Polk’s Potlatch Parade, 1911","d":"2014-02-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/02/21/seattle-now-then-polks-potlatch-parade-1911/","lat":47.6147,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place_approx","x":"A float for the 1911 Potlatch parade carries piggyback a smaller 1897 version of a Polk City Directory on a much bigger 1911 copy. The fourteen years between them is meant to symbolize the growth of the city since the Alaskan/Yukon gold rush of 1897 that the Golden Potlatch of 1911 was created to commemorate.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/potlatch-parade-1911-polks-directory-float-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle General Hospital","d":"2014-02-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/02/28/seattle-now-then-seattle-general-hospital/","lat":47.60585,"lon":-122.33127,"c":"addr","x":"Looking northwest to Seattle General Hospital at the northwest corner of Fifth Avenue and Marion Street, circa 1909.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/seattle-general-hospital-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Unitarian Drama","d":"2014-03-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/03/07/seattle-now-then-unitarian-drama/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"First dedicated in 1889 by Seattle's Unitarians, the congregation soon needed a larger sanctuary and moved to Capitol Hill. Here on 7th Avenue, their first home was next used for a great variety of events, including a temporary home for the Christian Church, a concert hall for the Ladies Musical Club, and a venue for political events like anarchist Emma Goldman's visit to Seattle in 1910. (Complim","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/unitarian-church-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"The Minor/Collins Home on First Hill","d":"2014-03-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/03/15/seattle-now-then-the-minorcollins-home-on-first-hill/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1887, the Minor-Collins Home at the northeast corner of Minor Avenue and Cherry Street was one of the grandest and longest surviving pioneer mansions on First Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/minor-collins-home-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"A Methodist Revival on Union Street","d":"2014-03-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/03/22/seattle-now-then-a-methodist-revival-on-union-street/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"The \"then\" photo looks southeast across Union Street to the old territorial university campus. It was recorded in the Fall of 1907, briefly before the old park-like campus was transformed into a grand commercial property, whose rents still support the running of the University of Washington.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/methodist-revival-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Madison’s Lost Poplars","d":"2014-03-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/03/29/seattle-now-then-madisons-lost-poplars/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"Looking west on Madison Street from Seventh Avenue circa 1909.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/7th-and-madison-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Two Views from the Needle (or, A Stitch in Time)","d":"2014-04-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/04/05/seattle-now-then-two-views-from-the-needle-or-a-stitch-in-time/","lat":47.6205,"lon":-122.3493,"c":"place_approx","x":"The Seattle Central Business District in 1962. I found this panorama mixed in with the Kodachrome slides photographed by Lawton Gowey. It was most likely taken by my helpful friend Lawton, who died in 1983, or Robert Bradley, Lawton's friend in the then active Seattle Camera Club.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/cbdistrict-pan-from-the-space-needle-1962-now-mr2.jpg"},{"t":"The Littlefield Apartments","d":"2014-04-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/04/12/seattle-now-then-the-littlefield-apartments/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"We have by three years or four missed the centenary for this distinguished brick pile, the Littlefield Apartments on Capitol Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/littlefield-apts-205-19th-ave-n-mr-then.jpg"},{"t":"A Shoebox on Fifth","d":"2014-04-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/04/19/seattle-now-then-a-shoebox-on-fifth/","lat":47.61312,"lon":-122.33821,"c":"addr","x":"Thanks again and again to Lawton Gowey for another contribution to this feature, this ca. 1917 look into a fresh Denny Regrade and nearly new \"office-factory\" at 1921 Fifth Avenue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/shoebox-on-5th-mr-then.jpg"},{"t":"Post Office Teams on University Street","d":"2014-04-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/04/26/seattle-now-then-post-office-teams-on-university-street/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Looking west from First Avenue down the University Street viaduct to the waterfront, ca. 1905. Post Office teams and their drivers pose beside the Arlington Hotel, which was then also headquarters for mail delivery in Seattle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/p-o-teams-on-university-st-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"A Late Latona Bridge","d":"2014-05-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/05/03/seattle-now-then-a-late-latona-bridge/","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place_approx","x":"The historical view looks directly south into the Latona addition's business district on Sixth Ave. NE. from the Northern Pacific's railroad bridge, now part of the Burke Gilman Recreation Trail.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/late-latona-bridge-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"The Post-Fire Post-Intelligencer","d":"2014-05-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/05/10/seattle-now-then-the-post-fire-post-intelligencer/","lat":47.621,"lon":-122.355,"c":"place","x":"In the late afternoon and evening of Seattle's Great Fire day, June 6, 1889, Leigh and Lizzie Hunt's home at the northwest corner of Fourth Avenue and Columbia Street was, within a few hours, arranged to accommodate the family's business, The Seattle Post-Intelligencer newspaper.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/post-intelligencer-post-fire-thenmr.jpg"},{"t":"The Ship Canal Bridge","d":"2014-05-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/05/17/seattle-now-then-the-ship-canal-bridge/","lat":47.658,"lon":-122.404,"c":"place","x":"Long-time Wallingford resident Victor Lygdman looks south through the work-in-progress on the Lake Washington Ship Canal Bridge during the summer of 1959. Bottom-right are the remnants of the Latona business and industrial district, including the Wayland Mill and the Northlake Apartments, replaced now with Ivar's Salmon House and its parking.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/lake-wa-freeway-bridge-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"A Hotel at Pike and Boren","d":"2014-05-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/05/24/seattle-now-then-a-hotel-at-pike-and-boren/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"Beginning with the Reynolds, three hotels have taken tenancy in this ornate three-story brick block at the northeast corner of Boren Avenue and Pike Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/hotel-reynolds-ne-cor-boren-pike-mr.jpg"},{"t":"The Pike Place Corner Market Building","d":"2014-05-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/05/31/seattle-now-then-the-pike-place-market-building/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"In this April morning record of the 1975 \"Rain or Shine Public Market Paint-in,\" above the artists, restoration work has begun with the gutting of the Corner Market Building.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/pike-market-paint-in-1975-mr-then.jpg"},{"t":"The Lake Union Dam Washout","d":"2014-06-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/06/07/seattle-now-then-the-lake-union-dam-washout/","lat":47.648,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"From the Fremont Bridge, this subject looks east northeast* across the torrent that followed the washout of the Fremont Dam in the early afternoon of March 13, 1914. Part of the Bryant Lumber and Shingle Mill appears left-of-center. The north end of the Stone Way Trestle appears in the upper right corner.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/fremont-dam-washout-3-13-14-mrthen.jpg"},{"t":"The Gatewood Lodge","d":"2014-06-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/06/14/seattle-now-then-the-gatewood-lodge/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place_approx","x":"The Gatewood Craftsman Lodge was built on a road, in a neighborhood, and near a public school all named for the developer Carlisle Gatewood, who also lived in the neighborhood. The three women posing in the third floor's open windows are the Clark sisters, Jean, Dorothy and Peggy, members of the family that moved into the home in the late 1930s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/gatewood-then.jpg"},{"t":"Kinnear Park","d":"2014-06-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/06/21/seattle-now-then-kinnear-park/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place_approx","x":"For his May Day, 1900 portrait of the Seattle City Council, the photographer, Anders Wilse, planted them, like additions to the landscape, on the lawn somewhere in the upper part of Kinnear Park.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/kinnear-park-inspection-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Spokane Street from West Seattle","d":"2014-06-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/06/28/seattle-now-then-spokane-street-from-west-seattle/","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"In 1852 many of Seattle's first pioneers removed from Alki Point by dugout canoe for the deeper and safer harbor along the east shore of Elliott Bay (our central waterfront). About a half-century later any hope or expectation that the few survivors among these pioneers could readily visit Alki Beach and Point by land were fulfilled with the timber quays and bridges along Spokane Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/spokane-st-lk-e-fm-admiral-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"A “New Deal” for Hard Times","d":"2014-07-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/07/05/seattle-now-then-a-new-deal-for-hard-times/","lat":47.578,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place_approx","x":"An Emergency Relief Administration wood pile took temporary quarters on the southeast corner of S. Alaska Street and 32nd Ave. S. in 1934.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/xw-e-r-a-wood-yard-w-trucks-at-32nd-and-s-alaska-mr-then.jpg"},{"t":"A Brooklyn Home Taken for the Cleaners","d":"2014-07-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/07/12/seattle-now-then-a-brooklyn-home-taken-for-the-cleaners/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.314,"c":"place","x":"When it was built in 1902, this box home, with classic Ionic pillars at the porch, was set above the northwest corner of the freshly graded Brooklyn Avenue and 47th Street in the University District.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/4703-brooklyn-ave-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"The “Finest Fruit”","d":"2014-07-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/07/18/seattle-now-then-the-finest-fruit/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place","x":"Local candy-maker A.W. Piper was celebrated here for his crème cakes and wedding cakes and also his cartoons. This sketch is of the 1882 lynching from the Maple trees beside Henry and Sara Yesler's home on James Street. Piper's bakery was nearby","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/the-finest-fruit-then-mr2.jpg"},{"t":"When the Circus Came to Town","d":"2014-07-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/07/25/seattle-now-then-when-the-circus-came-to-town/","lat":47.6212,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"In the first years of the twentieth century, visiting circuses most often used these future Seattle Center acres to raise their big tops. After 1911 the favored circus site was moved to the then freshly-cleared Denny Regrade neighborhood","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/equestrian-puzzle-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"The Fremont Trolley Barn","d":"2014-08-02","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/08/02/seattle-now-then-the-fremont-trolley-barn/","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place","x":"One of a few photographs recording from different prospects the Fremont trolley car barn on Dec.11, 1936. North 35th Street, on the right, was originally named Blewett for Edward and Carrie Blewett. In 1888 the couple, fresh from Fremont, Nebraska, first named and promoted Fremont as a Seattle neighborhood. That year Fremont also got its lumber mill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/femont-car-barn-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Salmon Bay","d":"2014-08-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/08/09/seattle-now-then-salmon-bay/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"Captioned Salmon Bay, 1887, this is most likely very near the eastern end of the bay where it was fed by Ross Creek, the Lake Union outlet.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/salmon-bay-lowman-album-1887-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"The Arkona at First and Denny","d":"2014-08-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/08/16/seattle-now-then-the-arkona-at-first-and-denny/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"In 1913, or near to it, an unnamed photographer recorded this view southeast across the Lower Queen Anne corner of Denny Way and First Avenue North. Out of frame to the left, the northeast corner of this intersection was home then for the Burdett greenhouse and gardens. (We have include an advertisement for them below.) By its own claim, Burdett offered plants of all sorts, \"the largest and most c","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/denny-first-ca-1912-lk-se-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"End of the Line for Golden Gardens","d":"2014-08-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/08/23/seattle-now-then-end-of-the-line-for-golden-gardens/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place_approx","x":"A circa 1908 look northeast through the terminus of the Loyal Electric Street Railway line at the corner of now Northwest 85th Street, 32nd Ave. Northwest, and Loyal Way Northwest.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/end-of-the-line-for-golden-gardens-mr-then.jpg"},{"t":"Seattle Then & Now: The Youngstown Steel Mill","d":"2014-08-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/08/30/seattle-then-now-the-youngstown-steel-mill/","lat":47.55,"lon":-122.346,"c":"place","x":"The Seattle Times in its lengthy coverage of the then new Seattle Steel in the paper's Magazine Section for Sept. 10, 1905 – the year this photograph was recorded – noted that \"the plant itself is a series of strong, substantial, cavernous sheds, built for use, not for beauty.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/youngstown-steel-mill-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"Wallingford Rising","d":"2014-09-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/09/06/seattle-now-then-wallingford-rising/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Looking west down Ewing Street (North 34th) in 1907 with the nearly new trolley tracks on the left and a drainage ditch on the right to protect both the tracks and the still barely graded street from flooding.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/wallingford-34th-lk-w-thru-densmore-then.jpg"},{"t":"Third Avenue South","d":"2014-09-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/09/13/seattle-now-then-third-avenue-south/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"1934 was one of the worst years of the Great Depression. This look north on Third Avenue South through Main Street and the Second Avenue South Extension was recorded on Thursday, April 19th of that year. Business was generally dire, but especially here in this neighborhood south of Yesler Way where there were many storefront vacancies.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/third-avenue-south-1934-looking-n-thru-main-street-then.jpg"},{"t":"The Occidental Hotel","d":"2014-09-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/09/20/seattle-now-then-the-occidental-hotel/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Seen here in 1887 through the intersection of Second Avenue and Yesler Way, the Occidental Hotel was then easily the most distinguished in Seattle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/occidental-hotel-1887-then-mr.jpg"},{"t":"First Hill and Yesler Terrace","d":"2014-09-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/09/27/seattle-now-then-first-hill-and-yesler-terrace/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place","x":"This Seattle Housing Authority photograph was recorded from the top of the Marine Hospital (now Pacific Tower) on the north head of Beacon Hill. It looks north to First Hill during the Authority's clearing of its southern slope for the building of the Yesler Terrace Public Housing.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/yesler-terrace-clearing-fm-marine-hospital-then-mr-1.jpg"},{"t":"Roll on, Columbia Street","d":"2014-10-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/10/04/seattle-now-then-roll-on-columbia-street/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.368,"c":"place","x":"In this 1887 look up Columbia Street from the waterfront is the bell tower of the fire station, tucked into the hill on the right. It would soon fail to halt the city's Great Fire of June 6, 1889. The station and everything between it and Elliott Bay were reduced to ashes, smoldering bricks and offshore pilings shortened like cigars.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/marion-st-lk-e-fm-waterfront-morford-ca-1888-copy-2.jpg"},{"t":"Third Avenue Regrade","d":"2014-10-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/10/11/seattle-now-then-third-avenue-regrade/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Looking north from Columbia Street over the construction pit for the Central Building. On the left is a rough section of the Third Avenue Regrade in the spring of 1907.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/third-ave-regrade-1907-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Leary Way","d":"2014-10-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/10/18/seattle-now-then-leary-way/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"With his or her back to the original Ballard business district, an unnamed photographer looks southeast on Leary Way, most likely in 1936.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/leary-way-lk-s-to-17th-ave-nw-mr-dec-1-1936-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"On the Waterfront","d":"2014-10-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/10/25/seattle-now-then-on-the-waterfront/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"The driver, lower left, leads his team towards First Avenue up a planked incline on Madison Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/foot-of-madison-ca-1889-thenmr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Comet becomes Star","d":"2014-11-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/11/01/seattle-now-then-comet-becomes-star/","lat":47.60325,"lon":-122.31802,"c":"addr","x":"Faced, in part, with brick veneer and stucco, and opened in 191l, the Comet Apartments at 170 11th Avenue have made it nicely through their first century.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/comet-star-apts-11th-spruce-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Summit Avenue Hospital","d":"2014-11-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/11/08/seattle-now-then-the-summit-avenue-hospital/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"This detail from the prolific local photographer Asahel Curtis's photograph of the Smith/Rininger home at the northwest corner of Columbia Street and Summit Avenue dates from the early twentieth century when motorcars, rolling or parked, were still very rare on the streets of Seattle, including these on First Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/summit-ave-hospital-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Hotel York","d":"2014-11-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/11/15/seattle-now-then-the-hotel-york/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"The Hotel York at the northwest corner of Pike Street and First Avenue supplied beds on the American Plan for travelers and rooms for traveling hucksters.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/hotel-york-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Wall Street Pier","d":"2014-11-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/11/22/seattle-now-then-the-wall-street-pier/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.3508,"c":"place","x":"A circa 1912 look at the Wall Street finger pier from the foot, not of Wall, but Battery Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/wall-street-pier-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Seventh & Seneca","d":"2014-11-30","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/11/30/seattle-now-then-seventh-seneca/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3284,"c":"cross","x":"Looking north-northeast from a low knoll at the southwest corner of Seneca Street and Seventh Avenue, circa 1916. By 1925, a commercial automobile garage filled the vacant lot in the foreground. [Courtesy, Ron Edge]","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/seneca-7th-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Fourth and Pike","d":"2014-12-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/12/06/seattle-now-then-fourth-and-pike/","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.3345,"c":"cross","x":"This rare early record of the Fourth and Pike intersection was first found by Robert McDonald, both a state senator and history buff with a special interest in historical photography. He then donated this photograph – with the rest of his collection – to the Museum of History and Industry, whom we thank for its use.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/pike-fourth-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"1st and Virginia and an invitation!","d":"2014-12-13","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/12/13/seattle-now-then-1st-and-virginia-and-an-invitation/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"In 1910, a circa date for this look north on First Avenue across Virginia Street, the two corners on the east side of the intersection were still undeveloped – except for signs. The Terminal Sales Building, seen far right in Jean Sherrard's repeat, did not replace the billboards that crowd the sidewalk in the \"then\" until 1923. (Seattle Municipal Archive)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/first-ave-lk-n-thru-virginia-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Poetry and Prose at 1st and Madison","d":"2014-12-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/12/20/seattle-now-then-poetry-and-prose-at-1st-and-madison/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"Looking south on First Avenue from its northwest corner with Madison Street, circa 1905.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/star-palace-stevens-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"City Hall, 1908","d":"2014-12-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2014/12/27/seattle-now-then-city-hall-1908/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.332,"c":"place_approx","x":"This \"real photo postcard\" was sold on stands throughout the city. It was what it claimed to be; that is, its gray tones were real. If you studied them with magnification the grays did not turn into little black dots of varying sizes.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/frasch-city-hall-ca1908-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Bartell’s Motorcycle Courier","d":"2015-01-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/01/03/seattle-now-then-the-bartells-motorcycle-courier/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"A motorcycle courier for Bartell Drugs poses before the chain's Store No. 14, located in the Seaboard Building at the northeast corner of Fourth Avenue and Pike Street, circa 1929.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/bartell-motorcycle-courier-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Terry House at 3rd & James","d":"2015-01-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/01/10/seattle-now-then-the-terry-house-at-3rd-james/","lat":47.6028,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"cross","x":"When it was built in 1864 Charles and Mary Terry's home was considered the finest in Seattle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/terry-home-n-side-of-james-bet-3-4-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Home on ‘The Ave’","d":"2015-01-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/01/17/seattle-now-then-a-home-on-the-ave/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"First designated Columbus Street in the 1890 platting of the Brooklyn Addition, and next as 14th Avenue to conform with the Seattle grid, ‘The Ave,' still its most popular moniker, was renamed University Way by contest in 1919. This trim bungalow at 3711 University Way sat a few lots north of Lake Union's Portage Bay.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/3711-university-way-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"‘Friends of the Market’ Protest at City Hall","d":"2015-01-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/01/24/seattle-now-then-friends-of-the-market-protest-at-city-hall/","lat":47.621,"lon":-122.355,"c":"place_approx","x":"Friends of the Market president, architect Victor Steinbrueck, leads a cadre of Friends marching for Market preservation in front of the Seattle City Hall most likely on March 18, 1971.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/friends-of-the-market-protest-city-hall-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Moveable Fiesta","d":"2015-01-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/01/31/seattle-now-then-a-moveable-fiesta/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Sitting on a small triangle at the odd northwest corner of Third Avenue and the Second Ave. S. Extension, the Fiesta Coffee Shop was photographed and captioned, along with all taxable structures in King County, by Works Progress Administration photographers during the lingering Great Depression of the late 1930s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/fiesta-coffee-shop-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Protest in 1937","d":"2015-02-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/02/07/seattle-now-then-a-protest-in-1937/","lat":47.60376,"lon":-122.33358,"c":"addr","x":"Depression-era protestors climb Columbia Street sidewalk along-aside Seattle architect Harlan Thomas's elegant Seattle landmark that opened in 1925 as home to the by then already forty-three year old Seattle Chamber of Commerce.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/chamber-of-commerce-protest-on-columbia-st-1937-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Gardner Home on Boren Avenue","d":"2015-02-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/02/14/seattle-now-then-the-gardner-home-on-boren-avenue/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"Built in the early twentieth century at the northeast corner of Jefferson Street and Boren Avenue, Bertha and Frank Gardner's residence was large but not a mansion, as were many big homes on First Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/gardner-home-necor-jefferson-boren-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Stetson and Post Block","d":"2015-02-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/02/21/seattle-now-then-the-stetson-and-post-block/","lat":47.6005,"lon":-122.3345,"c":"place","x":"The photographer David Judkins arrived here in 1883 and recorded this portrait of \"Seattle's first apartment house\" sometime soon after.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/stetson-post-business-block-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Boone Home","d":"2015-02-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/02/28/seattle-now-then-the-boone-home/","lat":47.6334,"lon":-122.358,"c":"place","x":"Sometime around 1890, George Moore, one of Seattle's most prolific early photographers, recorded this portrait of the home of the architect (and Daniel Boone descendent) William E. Boone. In the recently published second edition of Shaping Seattle Architecture, the book's editor, UW Professor of Architecture Jeffry Karl Ochsner, sketches William E. Boone's life and career. Ochsner adds, \"Boone was","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/william-boone-home-then-mr2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Going Postal at Marion & Western","d":"2015-03-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/03/07/seattle-now-then-going-postal-and-marion-western/","lat":47.647,"lon":-122.452,"c":"place","x":"Arthur Denny named both Marion and James Streets for his invalid brother, James Marion Denny, who was too ill to accompany the \"Denny Party\" from Oregon to Puget Sound in 1851.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/u-s-mail-wagon-at-western-marion-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The SINGULAR TRAFFIC TOWER at FOURTH and PIKE","d":"2015-03-14","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/03/14/seattle-now-then-the-singular-traffic-tower-at-fourth-and-pike/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Looking west on Pike Street from Fourth Avenue, the variety in the first block of this retail district includes the Rhodes Bros. Ten Cent Store, Mendenhall's Kodaks, Fountain Pens and Photo Supplies, Remick's Song and Gift Shop, the Lotus Confectionary, Fahey-Brockman's Clothiers, where, one may \"buy upstairs and save $10.00\".","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/pike-4th-traffic-control-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Anderson Hall","d":"2015-03-21","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/03/21/seattle-now-then-anderson-hall/","lat":47.6499,"lon":-122.3082,"c":"place","x":"Named for a lumberman, and still home for the UW's School of Environmental and Forest Sciences, the upper floor's high-ceilinged halls, including the Forest Club Room behind Anderson Hall's grand Gothic windows, were described for us by the department's gregarious telephone operator as \"very popular and Harry Potterish.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/anderson-hall-uw-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"“Murder” on Aurora","d":"2015-03-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/03/28/seattle-now-then-murder-on-aurora/","lat":47.65,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place","x":"Like violence in a classic Greek play, the carnage suggested by this 1934 crash scene on the then new Aurora speedway was kept off stage, either behind the city's official photographer, or in the county morgue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/aurora-ave-divider-wreckage-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"St. Vinnie’s in Belltown","d":"2015-04-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/04/04/seattle-now-then-st-vinnies-in-belltown/","lat":47.6147,"lon":-122.3464,"c":"place","x":"St. Vincent de Paul's first storefront opened in 1926 in Belltown's grand clapboard hostelry at the corner of First and Battery. Originally the Bellevue Hotel, it's reduced here to the \"house keeping and transient rooms\" of the Bay State Hotel. (MOHAI)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/st-vincent-1st-store-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Swedish Baptists in Ballard","d":"2015-04-10","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/04/10/seattle-now-then-swedish-baptists-in-ballard/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1910, Ballard's big brick church on the northwest corner of 20th Avenue NW and NW 63rd Street lost the top of its soaring tower following the earthquake of Nov. 12, 1939.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/swedish-baptist-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"First Hill Row Houses","d":"2015-04-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/04/18/seattle-now-then-first-hill-row-houses/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"At the northwest corner of Columbia Street and Boren Avenue, two of the more ordinary housing stock on First Hill in the 1890s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/first-hill-row-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Seattle Fire Ruins Redux","d":"2015-04-25","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/04/25/seattle-now-then-seattle-fire-ruins-redux/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place_approx","x":"The ruins left by Seattle's Great Fire of June 6, 1889, included a large neighborhood of warehouses and factories built on timber quays over the tides. Following the fire the quays were soon restored with new capping and planking. A close look on the far-right will reveal some of this construction on the quays underway.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/great-fire-waterfront-ruins-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Steps to the Harbor","d":"2015-05-01","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/05/01/seattle-now-then-steps-to-the-harbor/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Following the city's Great Fire of 1889, a trestle was built on University Street, between Front Street (First Avenue) and Railroad Avenue (Alaskan Way). By the time Lawton Gowey photographed what remained of the timber trestle in 1982, it had been shortened and would soon be razed for the Harbor Steps seen in Jean Sherrard's repeat.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/university-st-ramp-at-western-1982-gowey-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Klondike Fever on First","d":"2015-05-09","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/05/09/seattle-now-then-klondike-fever-on-first/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place_approx","x":"During the few years of the Klondike Gold Rush, the streets of Seattle's business district were crowded with outfitters selling well-packed foods and gear to thousands of traveling men heading north to strike it rich – they imagined.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/outfitters-on-front-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Sinking Ship","d":"2015-05-16","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/05/16/seattle-now-then-the-sinking-ship/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"In Lawton Gowey's 1961 pairing, the Smith Tower (1914) was the tallest building in Seattle, and the Pioneer Square landmark Seattle Hotel (1890) had lost most of its top floor. (by Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/seattle-hotel-demolish-w-smith-tower-gowey-june-8-1961-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Louch Grocery on First Avenue","d":"2015-05-23","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/05/23/seattle-now-then-the-louch-grocery-on-first-avenue/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Charles Louch's grocery on First Avenue, north of Union Street, opened in the mid-1880s and soon prospered. It is possible – perhaps probable – that one of the six characters posing here is Louch – more likely one of the two suited ones on the right than the aproned workers on the left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/louch-store-1880s-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Norway Hall","d":"2015-05-29","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/05/29/seattle-now-then-norway-hall/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"The now century-old Norway Hall at the corner of Boren Avenue and Virginia Street opened in 1915, on May 17, Norwegian Independence Day.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/norway-hall-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Gethsemane Lutheran","d":"2015-06-06","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/06/06/seattle-now-then-gethsemane-lutheran/","lat":47.6166,"lon":-122.3372,"c":"place","x":"Swedish Lutheran (Gethsemane) Church's second sanctuary at the northeast corner of Ninth Avenue and Steward Street circa 1920, photo by Klaes Lindquist.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/gesthemane-lutheran-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Sarah Baker’s Hotel","d":"2015-06-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/06/12/seattle-now-then-sarah-bakers-hotel/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"A mix of workers, friends and guests pose together on the front porch of Sarah Frances Baker's hotel at the northeast corner of Third Avenue and Marion Street in 1895. Built ten years earlier by Martin and Elisabeth Stacy as their first mansion, the warring couple never lived in it. Used in the early 1890s by the Seattle Chamber of Commerce, followed by Baker and her hotel, the Second Empire style","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/sarah-bakers-hotel-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Ye Olde Totem Place","d":"2015-06-20","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/06/20/seattle-now-then-ye-olde-totem-place/","lat":47.58716,"lon":-122.38527,"c":"addr","x":"(click to enlarge photos) THEN: Totem Place, at 1750 Palm Ave. S.W., was home for Joseph Standley proprietor of Ye Old Curiosity Shop on Colman Dock. His death notice in The Seattle Times for Oct. 25, 1940 described the 86-year-old \"Daddy\" Standley as \"almost as much a part of Seattle's waterfront as the waves that dash against the seaweall.\" Joseph James, \"Daddy\" Standley's grandson, will welcome","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/ye-olde-home-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Silvian Apartments","d":"2015-06-27","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/06/27/seattle-now-then-the-silvian-apartments/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"An early portrait, circa 1911, of The Silvian Apartments, one of Capitol Hill's abiding architectural jewels.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/silvian-apts-then-mr2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Golden Potlatch on the Waterfront","d":"2015-07-04","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/07/04/seattle-now-then-golden-potlatch-on-the-waterfront/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"From boxcars and rooftops to the planks of Railroad Avenue, excitement builds for the ceremonial re-enactment of the S.S.Portland's 1897 landing with its \"ton of gold\" on the Seattle waterfront, the city's first Golden Potlatch Celebration. [Courtesy, Michael Maslan]","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/potlatch-watch-above-railroad-ave-now-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Seattle Fire, Three Weeks Later","d":"2015-07-11","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/07/11/seattle-now-then-the-seattle-fire-three-weeks-later/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place_approx","x":"Looking north-northeast from the corner of Main Street and Occidental Avenue two or three weeks after the city's Great Fire of June 6, 1889.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/occidental-main-1889-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Fire Below the Market","d":"2015-07-18","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/07/18/seattle-now-then-fire-below-the-market/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"The 1974 fire at the Municipal Market Building on the west side of Western Avenue did not hasten the demise of the by then half-century old addition of the Pike Place Market. It had already been scheduled for demolition.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/municipal-market-fire-9-23-74-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Pontius Home","d":"2015-07-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/07/24/seattle-now-then-the-pontius-home/","lat":47.6173,"lon":-122.3478,"c":"place","x":"The Cascade neighborhood, named for its public grade school (1894), now long gone, might have been better named for the Pontius family. Immigrants from Ohio, they purchased many of the forested acres north of Denny Way and east of Fairview Avenue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/pontius-home-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Bagley Mansion","d":"2015-07-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/07/31/seattle-now-then-the-bagley-mansion/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"Constructed in 1885, the Alice and Clarence Bagley mansion was the first big home built on the south slope of Queen Anne Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/bagley-home-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Sorrento Hotel","d":"2015-08-07","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/08/07/seattle-now-then-the-sorrento-hotel/","lat":47.6079,"lon":-122.3245,"c":"place","x":"Through its now long life as a local landmark, the Sorrento Hotel, at the northwest corner of Madison Street and Terry Avenue, has been variously referred to as Seattle's \"Honeymoon Hotel,\" its \"Most Romantic Hotel,\" a \"remnant of Seattle's original cocktail culture,\" and now, more often, \"Seattle's original boutique hotel.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/sorrento-late-construction-web.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Virginia Mason","d":"2015-08-15","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/08/15/seattle-now-then-virginia-mason/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3247,"c":"place","x":"An early view of Virginia Mason Hospital, which opened in the fall of 1920 at the northwest corner of Terry Avenue and Spring Street. In 1980 for its anniversary, the clinic-hospital could make the proud statement that it had \"spanned sixty years and four city blocks.\" Courtesy Lawton Gowey","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/virginia-mason-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Frances Hotel (aka 5th Avenue regrade)","d":"2015-08-22","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/08/22/seattle-now-then-the-frances-hotel-aka-5th-avenue-regrade/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Looking north from Yesler Way over the Fifth Avenue regrade in 1911. Note the Yesler Way Cable rails and slot at the bottom.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/frances-hotel-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Return of the Homestead","d":"2015-08-28","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/08/28/seattle-now-then-return-of-the-homestead/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place_approx","x":"Included among the several detailed photos taken for the Bernards of their new and yet rustic Fir Lodge, was this one of the living room with its oversized fireplace and the piano on which Marie, their older daughter, learned to play well enough to concertize.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/fir-lodge-hearth-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Schmitz Park","d":"2015-09-05","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/09/05/seattle-now-then-schmitz-park/","lat":47.568,"lon":-122.403,"c":"place","x":"Looking southeast from above Alki Avenue, the Schmitz Park horizon is serrated by the oldest trees in the city. The five duplexes clustered on the right were built 1919-1921 by Ernest and Alberta Conklin. Ernest died in 1924, but Alberta continued to live there until well past 1932, the year this photograph was recorded. (Seattle Municipal Archives.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/towards-schmidt-pk-then-mr-5-24-32.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Wallingford Wall at the Latona Knoll","d":"2015-09-12","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/09/12/seattle-now-then-the-wallingford-wall-at-the-latona-knoll/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"From 1909 to the mid-late 1920s, the precipitous grade separation between the upper and lower parts of NE 40th Street west of 7th Ave. NE was faced with a timber wall. When the wall was removed, the higher part of NE 40th was shunted north, cutting into the lawns of the homes beside it.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ne-40th-st-lk-w-fm-7th-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Yesler (No sir!)","d":"2015-09-19","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/09/19/seattle-now-then-yesler-no-sir/","lat":47.60165,"lon":-122.3237,"c":"addr","x":"The address written on the photograph is incorrect. This is 717 E. Washington Street and not 723 Yesler Way. We, too, were surprised.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/717-washington-street-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Row House at 6th and Pine","d":"2015-09-26","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/09/26/seattle-now-then-a-row-house-at-6th-and-pine/","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The row house at the southwest corner of 6th Avenue and Pine Street in its last months, ca. 1922-23. (Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/row-house-6-pine-swcor-then-mr2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A View of Lake Union","d":"2015-10-03","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/10/03/seattle-now-then-a-view-of-lake-union/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"A.J. McDonald's panorama of Lake Union and its surrounds dates from the early 1890s. It was taken from First Hill, looking north from near the intersection of Terry Avenue and Union Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/mcdonald-lk-union-pan-lk-n-ca-1892-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Mill Street at Pioneer Place","d":"2015-10-08","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/10/08/seattle-now-then-mill-street-near-pioneer-square/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"The original for this scene of a temporary upheaval on Mill Street (Yesler Way) was one of many historical prints given to the Museum of History and Industry many years ago by the Charles Thorndike estate. Thorndike was one of Seattle's history buffs extraordinaire.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/mill-street-clapboards-ca-1883-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A View from the Cambridge Hotel","d":"2015-10-17","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/10/17/seattle-now-then-a-view-from-the-cambridge-hotel/","lat":47.61164,"lon":-122.33042,"c":"addr","x":"The city's north end skyline in 1923 looking northwest from the roof of the then new Cambridge Apartments at 9th Avenue and Union Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/cambridge-roof-pan-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The North Seattle Trolley Yard","d":"2015-10-24","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/10/24/seattle-now-then-the-north-seattle-trolley-yard/","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place_approx","x":"Looking west from the southwest corner of 6th Ave. N. and Mercer St. to the trolley barn and yards for the (renamed in 1919) Seattle Municipal Railway in 1936.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/north-seattle-car-barn-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"“Cook with Gas”","d":"2015-10-31","u":"http://pauldorpat.com/2015/10/31/seattle-now-then-cook-with-gas/","lat":47.624,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"This portrait of the Seattle Gas Company's storage tank dates from the spring of 1907, which explains its somewhat steeper topography. In 1911, both Republican Street, here on the right, and 9th Avenue N. were lowered to a grade close to that of Westlake Avenue, which is behind the photographer.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/9th-republican-5-7-1907-then-mr2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"An Approach to the Campus","d":"2015-11-07","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/11/07/seattle-now-then-an-approach-to-the-campus/","lat":47.653,"lon":-122.321,"c":"place","x":"sliver of the U.W. campus building called the Applied Physics Laboratory appears on the far right of this 1940 look east towards the U.W. campus from the N.E. 40th Street off-ramp from the University Bridge. While very little other than the enlarged laboratory survives in the fore and mid-grounds, much on the horizon of campus buildings and apartments still stand.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/from-ne-fortieth-to-lincoln-way-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Green Lake Midwife","d":"2015-11-14","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/11/14/seattle-now-then-a-green-lake-midwife/","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Midwife Alice Wood Ellis, far right, joins her mother and two children on the front lawn of their half-finished home in the East Green Lake neighborhood, ca. 1901. Courtesy Carol Solle","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/green-lake-midwife-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Dutch Ned","d":"2015-11-21","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/11/21/seattle-now-then-dutch-ned/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Pioneer mailman Dutch Ned poses on his horse on Cherry Street. The ca. 1880 view looks east over First Avenue when it was still named Front Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/dutch-ned-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Rattlesnake Lake","d":"2015-11-28","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/11/28/seattle-now-then-rattlesnake-lake/","lat":47.4339,"lon":-121.7785,"c":"place","x":"Darius Kinsey's ca. 1914 panorama of the King County town of Cedar Falls (aka Moncton) set beside the unstable shore of Rattlesnake Lake.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/rattlesnake-lake-and-ridge-then-mr1.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Epler Block","d":"2015-12-05","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/12/05/seattle-now-then-the-epler-block/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The west side of Second Avenue between Columbia and Marion Streets was typical of the commercial district that was quick to develop after the city's Great Fire of 1889.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/epler-block-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Gas Works Park – A Haag Landscape","d":"2015-12-12","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/12/12/seattle-now-then-gas-works-park-a-haag-landscape/","lat":47.646,"lon":-122.3346,"c":"place","x":"The 1906-07 Gas Works at the north end of Lake Union went idle in 1956 when natural gas first reached Seattle by pipeline. In this photo, taken about fifteen years later, the Wallingford Peninsula is still home to the plant's abandoned and \"hanging gardens of metal.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/gas-works-park-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Randal Gravelle’s ‘Hooverville’","d":"2015-12-18","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/12/18/seattle-now-then-randal-gravelles-hooverville/","lat":47.587,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Unemployed men search for anything useful in land being reclaimed with city garbage used for fill on the tideflats. The date is March 6, 1937. The scene looks northwest from what was once near 7th Ave. S. and Forest Street, but is now inside the operations facilities for the Light Rail Division of Sound Transit. The Sears Department Store, now home of Starbucks Coffee Co., appears in the upper-lef","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/gravelles-hooverville-then2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Too High and Too Steep","d":"2015-12-26","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2015/12/26/seattle-now-then-too-high-and-too-steep/","lat":47.6147,"lon":-122.3464,"c":"place","x":"The northeast corner of Belltown's intersection of Blanchard Street and Fourth Avenue was about 100 feet higher than it is now. The elegant late-Victorian clutters of the Burwell homes' interiors are also featured on the noted blog.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/4th-and-blanchard-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"McKay Ford on Westlake","d":"2016-01-09","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/01/09/seattle-now-then-mckay-ford/","lat":47.62,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"William O. McKay opened show rooms on Westlake in July of 1923. After fifty-seven years of selling Fords, the dealership turned to the cheaper and more efficient Subaru. Now reconstructed, the old Ford showroom awaits a new tenant.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/mckay-ford-1949-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Prince Rupert Hotel","d":"2016-01-15","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/01/15/seattle-now-then-the-prince-rupert-hotel/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"Built quickly in the winter of 1906-07, the Prince Rupert Hotel faced Boren Avenue from the third lot north of Pike Street. About fifty-five years later it was razed for the I-5 Freeway.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/prince-rupert-hotel-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Mayor Brown’s Garage in Redmond","d":"2016-01-23","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/01/23/seattle-now-then-mayor-browns-garage-in-redmond/","lat":47.615,"lon":-122.086,"c":"place_approx","x":"From studying both aerial and tax photos, Redmond historian Tom Hitzroth figures that the bell tower on the roof of Brown's Garage was removed between 1936 and 1938. (Most likely it was used to alert the town's volunteer fire department.) By then Mayor Bill Brown had sold his garage while keeping his mayoral chair.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/browns-garage-in-redmond-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Bank of Redmond","d":"2016-01-30","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/01/30/seattle-now-then-the-bank-of-redmond/","lat":47.674,"lon":-122.1215,"c":"place","x":"Redmond reaped its first bank in 1911 at the pioneer corner of Cleveland Avenue and Leary Way.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/redmond-bank-then-mrr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Baker’s Dock aka The Ecclefechan","d":"2016-02-06","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/02/06/seattle-now-then-bakers-dock-aka-the-ecclefechan/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"Looking south from the Schwabacher Wharf to the Baker Dock and along the Seattle waterfront rebuilt following the city's Great Fire of June 6, 1889.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/bakers-dock-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Ballard’s Bascule Bridge","d":"2016-02-13","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/02/13/seattle-now-then-ballards-bascule-bridge-2/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"James Lee, for many years an official photographer for Seattle's public works department, looks south over Ballard's Salmon Bay a century ago. Queen Anne Hill marks the horizon, with a glimpse of Magnolia on the far right.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/ballards-bascule-bridge-future-path.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Big Snow in Ballard, 1916","d":"2016-02-20","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/02/20/seattle-now-then-big-snow-in-ballard-1916/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"Ballard photographer Fred Peterson looks south-southeast on Ballard Avenue on February 3rd or 4th, 1916.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/1916-big-snow-onballard-ave-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Seward Street, Juneau, Alaska","d":"2016-02-27","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/02/27/seattle-now-then-seward-street-juneau-alaska/","lat":58.3019,"lon":-134.4197,"c":"place","x":"Photographer Frank LaRoche arrived in Seattle a few weeks after its Great Fire of 1889. Through the 1890s he made scores of round-trips to the Klondike, including this visit to the Juneau intersection of Seward Avenue and Front Street. (Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/juneau-seward-street-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Albert Braun’s Brewery in Georgetown","d":"2016-03-05","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/03/05/seattle-now-then-albert-brauns-brewery-in-georgetown/","lat":47.547,"lon":-122.322,"c":"place","x":"Extended thanks to Ron Edge and his maps and aerials for properly siting Braun's Brewery, to collector Dan Kerlee for letting us use this company portrait, and to Gary Flynn, the Bellingham-based breweriana collector and brewery historian.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/albert-braun-brewery-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The St. James Dome Collapse","d":"2016-03-12","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/03/12/seattle-now-then-the-st-james-dome-collapse/","lat":47.581,"lon":-122.408,"c":"place","x":"Of the three largest Seattle roofs – the Alki Point Natatorium, a grandstand section of the U.W.'s Denny Field, and the St. James Cathedral dome – that crashed under the weight of the \"Northwest Blizzard\" in February 1916, the last was the grandest and probably loudest. It fell \"with a crashing roar that was heard many blocks distant.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/st-james-dome-crash-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Juneau Street Footbridge","d":"2016-03-19","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/03/19/seattle-now-then-the-juneau-street-footbridge/","lat":47.578,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place","x":"As the caption at the bottom allows, the Juneau Street footbridge opened for pedestrians on March 26,1915. It crossed the main track lines – not spurs – of three railroads and reached east from the Georgetown business district to a sprawling neighborhood of workers' homes on the gentle slope of the Beacon Hill ridge.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/juneau-street-footbridge-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"West Woodland Neighbors","d":"2016-03-26","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/03/26/seattle-now-then-west-woodland-neighbors/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"This look west from the West Woodland neighborhood toward Ballard comes by way of the Museum of History and Industry, with some help from both Ron Edge and West Woodland historian Susan Pierce.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/west-woodland-jensen-home-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Lake Union","d":"2016-04-02","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/04/02/seattle-now-then-lake-union/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.314,"c":"place","x":"Samuel McKnight's early 1890s panorama of Lake Union also looks north into most of Seattle's seventeen square-mile annexation of 1891, when the city limits were pushed north from McGraw Street to 85th Street. Fremont, Edgewater, the future Wallingford, Latona, and Brooklyn (University District) were among the neighborhoods included.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/lake-union-by-mcknight-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"“We Love the Junction!”","d":"2016-04-09","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/04/09/seattle-now-then-we-love-the-junction/","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"Looking into West Seattle's Junction and north on California Ave. SW to its intersection with SW Alaska Street in 1941. The Hamm Building, is seen above the light-colored car, and the Campbell Building is at right, behind the G.O. Guy Drugs sign.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/we-love-the-junction-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"James Street Cable Cars","d":"2016-04-16","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/04/16/seattle-now-then-james-street-cable-cars/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place","x":"A half-century after they reached the top of First Hill, electric streets cars and cable cars prepare to leave it.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/james-street-cable-goodbye-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Great White Fleet, 1908","d":"2016-04-23","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/04/23/seattle-now-then-the-great-white-fleet-1908/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"About a year after he recorded this fashionable throng on Second Avenue celebrating the visit of President Theodore Roosevelt's Great White Fleet in the spring of 1908, Frank Nowell became the official photographer for Seattle's six-month-long Alaska Yukon and Pacific Exhibition in 1909.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/great-white-fleet-visit-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Normandie Apartments at Ninth and University","d":"2016-04-30","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/04/30/seattle-now-then-the-normandie-apartments-at-ninth-and-university/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1909-10 on one of First Hill's steepest slopes, the dark brick Normandie Apartments' three wings, when seen from the sky, resemble a bird in flight. (Lawton Gowey)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/normandie-apartments-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Georgetown Depot","d":"2016-05-07","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/05/07/seattle-now-then-the-georgetown-depot/","lat":47.547,"lon":-122.322,"c":"place","x":"The Oregon and Washington Railroad Georgetown Depot was built in 1910 about two blocks north of the Seattle Lighting Company's Gas Works, far-right.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/oregon-and-washington-rr-station-georgetown-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Hanson Avenue, 1913","d":"2016-05-14","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/05/14/seattle-now-then-hanson-avenue-1913/","lat":47.581,"lon":-122.408,"c":"place","x":"First named Hanson Avenue, for Hans Hanson, an Alki Point settler, 63rd Ave. SW extends about a third of a mile across the Point. In 1908 an electric trolley line first crossed the Point on 63rd. The tracks can be found here in the graded dirt street. This view looks north.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/hanson-st-ca-1913-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Row of Houses on Broadway","d":"2016-05-21","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/05/21/seattle-now-then-row-of-houses-on-broadway/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.321,"c":"place","x":"A King County Assessor's tax photo from 1937 aims south on Broadway from Marion Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/a-broadway-row-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Seattle’s First Big Fire","d":"2016-05-28","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/05/28/seattle-now-then-seattles-first-big-fire/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"Ruins from the fire of July 26, 1879, looking west on Yesler's dock from the waterfront.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/first-big-fire-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Florists’ Row at 9th & Union","d":"2016-06-04","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/06/04/seattle-now-then-florists-row-at-9th-union/","lat":47.6122,"lon":-122.3245,"c":"cross","x":"Built in the early twentieth century, this two-story corner block of storefronts and apartments was one of the victims of the Interstate-5 Freeway construction in the early 1960s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/9th-union-1937-tax-pix-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Music at Commercial and Main","d":"2016-06-11","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/06/11/seattle-now-then-music-at-commercial-and-main/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place_approx","x":"An unidentified brass band poses at the intersection of Commercial Street (First Ave S.) and Main Street during the 1883 celebration for the completion of the transcontinental Northern Pacific Railroad.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/brass-band-1883-villiards-visit-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Kenney Home","d":"2016-06-19","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/06/19/seattle-now-then-the-kenney-home/","lat":47.571,"lon":-122.387,"c":"place","x":"(click to enlarge photos) Seattle's famed architects John Graham and David John Myers joined to design the Kenney Home. This view, prior to 1927 when the Seattle Streetcar Co. trestle was removed, looks north from the corner of SW Othello Street and 47th Avenue SW. (Courtesy Richard Wilkens) NOW: Descendants Stuart and Michele Kenney pose at the same intersection, sans trestle. The former Ashton G","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/kenny-home-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"An Eastlake Cutie","d":"2016-06-25","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/06/25/seattle-now-then-an-eastlake-cutie/","lat":47.639,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"A carpenter's jewel with Victorian ornaments recorded by a tax assessor's photographer in 1936, nestles at 615 Eastlake beside the surviving Jensen Apartments, aka the O'Donnell Building, on the left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/615-eastlake-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Rhodes Mansion (with 2 Electric Cars)","d":"2016-07-02","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/07/02/seattle-now-then-the-rhodes-mansion-with-2-electric-cars/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"The ‘Seattle showplace' Rhodes mansion on Capitol Hill, ca. 1916.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/rhodes-home-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Making of Western Avenue","d":"2016-07-09","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/07/09/seattle-now-then-the-making-of-western-avenue/","lat":47.6173,"lon":-122.3478,"c":"place","x":"James P. Lee, Seattle's busy public works photographer of the early 20th century, recorded this 1922 look north from near the west end of Denny Way on the bluff above the then-forming Elliott Way.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/western-ave-west-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Denny’s Swale","d":"2016-07-16","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/07/16/seattle-now-then-dennys-swale/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"We imagine that the photographer A.J. McDonald waited for one of his subjects, the cable car to Queen Anne Hill, to reach the intersection of Second Ave. N. and Aloha Street below him before snapping this panorama in the mid- 1890s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/dennys-swale-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Digging the Fremont Canal","d":"2016-07-23","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/07/23/seattle-now-then-digging-the-fremont-canal/","lat":47.658,"lon":-122.404,"c":"place","x":"This panorama could have used a tower (or drone) to better survey the size of the June 1, 191l, crowd gathered in Fremont/Ross to celebrate the beginning of construction on the Lake Washington Ship Canal.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/canal-dig-celebration-in-fremont-crop.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Market – ‘An Honest Place in a Phony Time’","d":"2016-07-30","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/07/30/seattle-now-then-the-market-an-honest-place-in-a-phony-time/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"A circa 1920 look north along the tiled roofline of the Pike Place Market's North Arcade, which is fitted into the slender block between Pike Place, on the right, and Western Avenue, on the left.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/pike-market-north-arcade-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Plymouth Congregational Church at 3rd and University","d":"2016-08-06","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/08/06/seattle-now-then-the-plymouth-congregational-church-at-3rd-and-university/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Plymouth Congregational Church barely reached maturity – twenty-one years – when it was torn down in 1913 for construction of the equally grand but less prayerful Pantages Theatre, also at the northeast corner of Third Avenue and University Street. (Museum of History & Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/plymouth-congregational-church-ca-1903-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Mark Tobey in the Market","d":"2016-08-13","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/08/13/seattle-now-then-mark-tobey-in-the-market/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Mark Tobey, almost certainly Seattle's historically most celebrated artist, poses in the early 1960s with some Red Delicious apples beside the Sanitary Market in the Pike Place Market.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/mark-tobey-in-market-w-apples-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Waldorf Apartments","d":"2016-08-20","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/08/20/seattle-now-then-the-waldorf-apartments/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Encouraged by the rapid growth of Seattle's business and retail districts to the north, the Waldorf, then the biggest apartment house in town, was raised on the northeast corner of Pike Street and 7th Avenue in 1906-7.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/hotel-waldorf-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Fire Station No. 5 (or ‘You’ll Like Tacoma’)","d":"2016-08-27","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/08/27/seattle-now-then-fire-station-no-5-or-youll-like-tacoma/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"This post-1889 waterfront block of sheds and ships was replaced in 1911 by the Grand Trunk Pacific Dock, described at the time as \"the largest wooden finger pier in North America.\" The exception was Fire Station No. 5 on the left at the foot of Madison Street. A brick station replaced it in 1913. (Museum of History & Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/youll-like-tacoma-now-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Third & Virginia, 1936","d":"2016-09-03","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/09/03/seattle-now-then-third-virginia-1936/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"The five buildings shown here on the west side of Third Avenue south of Virginia Street have endured with few changes since the ‘then' photo was snapped in 1936. The exception is the smallest, far-right, the Virginian Tavern now stripped for an open garage at Third's southwest corner with Virginia Street. The six-story Hardon Hall Apartments, at the center of the five, was renovated in 2006 for lo","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/third-virginia-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Delta Gamma on the Ave","d":"2016-09-10","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/09/10/seattle-now-then-delta-gamma-on-the-ave/","lat":47.66332,"lon":-122.31302,"c":"addr","x":"The first house for Delta Gamma at N.E. 4730 University Way.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/delta-gamma-sorority-1904-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Yesler’s Wharf, 1891","d":"2016-09-17","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/09/17/seattle-now-then-yeslers-wharf-1891/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"F. Jay Haynes recorded this ca. 1891 look up the Seattle waterfront and it's railroad trestles most likely for a report to his employer, the Northern Pacific Railroad.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/yeslers-wharf-ca-1891-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Westlake Triangle (aka The Silverstone Block)","d":"2016-09-24","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/09/24/seattle-now-then-the-westlake-triangle-aka-the-silverstone-block/","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"This Webster and Stevens studio photo dates from either late 1917 or early 1918. The grand Frederick and Nelson Department store, rising above Fifth Avenue, has not yet reached its sumptuous Sept. 3. 1918 opening. In the foreground, the much smaller but also elegant flatiron building, bordered by Pine Street, in the foreground, and Westlake and Fifth Avenues to the sides, was razed and replaced al","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/pine-westalke-5th-flatiron-block-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Post Alley Curve","d":"2016-10-01","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/10/01/seattle-now-then-the-post-alley-curve/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"The Pike Place Market's irregular block shapes and bluff-side topography joined to create a multi-level campus of surprising places, such as this covered curve routing Post Alley up into the Market. Here, in 1966, the \"gent's\" entrance to Seattle's first Municipal Rest Room (1908) is closed with red tape and a sign reading \"Toilet room, closed temporarily for repairs.\" The Market was then generall","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/post-alley-curve-frank-shaw-5-1-66-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"‘The Sunset Board Room’","d":"2016-10-08","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/10/08/seattle-now-then-the-sunset-board-room/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"Completed in 1900, the Graham mansion on First Hill at the southwest corner of 9th Avenue and Columbia Street is getting some roof repairs in this 1937 photo looking south across Columbia Street. It was razed in the 1966 for a parking lot by its last owner and neighbor, the Catholic archdiocese.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/the-sunset-board-room-1937-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The First (and Forgotten) Alki Natatorium","d":"2016-10-15","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/10/15/seattle-now-then-the-first-and-forgotten-alki-natatorium/","lat":47.581,"lon":-122.408,"c":"place","x":"The first Alki Natatorium was built in 1905 at Alki Point eight years before the lighthouse.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/alki-nat-detail-of-s-facade-w-wagon-web.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Society Theatre on Broadway","d":"2016-10-22","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/10/22/seattle-now-then-the-society-theatre-on-broadway/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"Capitol Hill's Society Theatre first opened its doors in 1911. This record of it most likely dates from 1920, the first year in which the theatre could have shown the four films promoted with sensational posters near its front doors: the comedy \"Mary's Ankle,\" \"The Sagebrusher,\" a western, \"Silk Husbands and Calico Wives,\" and \"Everywoman,\" a feminist allegory appropriately filmed in 1919, on the ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/x-clip-house_peters_silk_husbands_and_calico_wives_film_daily_1919.png&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Big Stump","d":"2016-10-29","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/10/29/seattle-now-then-the-big-stump/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"Variously named the Giant Cedar Stump, the Big Arlington Stump, or just The Stump, this Snohomish Country roadside attraction was killed by a fire in 1893, reduced to stump size and tunneled in 1916, given a concrete base in 1922, and moved alongside the new Highway 99 in 1939, where it is shown here in 1940, long before its last move in 1971.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/big-cedar-stump-1940-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Broadway and Roy and The Deluxe","d":"2016-11-05","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/11/05/seattle-now-then-broadway-and-roy-and-the-deluxe/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.321,"c":"place","x":"Looking south on 10th Avenue E. to the freshly re-paved intersection where Broadway splits into itself and 10th Avenue North in 1932.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/broadway-and-roy-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Yakima Canyon","d":"2016-11-12","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/11/12/seattle-now-then-the-yakima-canyon/","lat":46.76,"lon":-120.47,"c":"place","x":"Hugh Paradise neither named nor dated his photograph looking down from a basalt cliff onto the Yakima River.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/paradises-yakima-canyon-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Jackson St. and First Avenue South","d":"2016-11-19","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/11/19/seattle-now-then-jackson-st-and-first-avenue-south/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"This view looking east from First Avenue South on Jackson Street in 1904, is still four years short of the Jackson Street Regrade during which the distant horizon line near 9th Avenue was lowered by more than 70 feet.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/jackson-east-fm-1st-1904-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Room with a View – Atop the WAC Roof","d":"2016-11-26","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/11/26/seattle-now-then-a-room-with-a-view-atop-the-wac-roof/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"We give this panorama from the roof of the Washington Athletic Club a circa date of 1961, the year that Horizon House, a First Hill retirement community, first opened its doors to residents at Ninth Avenue and University Street. The high-rise L-shaped Horizon stands top-center. (Lawton Gowey) CLICK TO ENLARGE","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/wac-lk-east-before-freeway2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Licton Springs","d":"2016-12-03","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/12/03/seattle-now-then-licton-springs/","lat":47.6985,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Before it became a city park, Licton Springs was run as a health spa. The distant home, left-of-center, at the northeast corner of N. 97th Street and Densmore Avenue N., survives in Jean Sherrard's repeat. It can be found on the left above the Y in the Licton Springs Park pathway. And the house on the hill can also be found below just above Jean's salutations, my response and Ron's llinks.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/licton-springs-mineral-baths-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"5th and Pike","d":"2016-12-10","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/12/10/seattle-now-then-5th-and-pike/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Looking east on Pike Street from Fifth Avenue early in the twentieth century.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/pike-5th-looking-east-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Third and Seneca","d":"2016-12-17","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/12/17/seattle-now-then-third-and-seneca/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Seattle's new – in 1910-11 – cluster-ball street lighting standards stand tall in this ca. 1911 look north on Third Avenue from Seneca Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/3rd-seneca-lk-nw-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"First and Seneca","d":"2016-12-24","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2016/12/24/seattle-now-then-first-and-seneca/","lat":47.68,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"An electric trolley heading north for Green Lake completes its crossing of Seneca Street, continuing its passage beside a diverse cluster of one small tailor shop – at the center – and four hotels named right-to-left, the Hotel Ramona, the Yates, the Yellowstone, and at the corner with University Street, the Hotel Diller.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/hotel-ramona-1st-and-seneca-ca-1906-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Ballard Fire Station ca. 1903","d":"2017-01-07","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/01/07/seattle-now-then-the-ballard-fire-station-ca-1903/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.321,"c":"place","x":"Ballard's short-lived fire station at the southwest corner of Broadway (NW Market Street) and Burke Avenue (Russell Ave. NW) circa 1903. Looking northwest the view includes, above the horses, a glimpse of Sypher's Hall, a rentable venue for playful and/or political events.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/ballard-fire-station-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Corgiat Building near Pioneer Square","d":"2017-01-14","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/01/14/seattle-now-then-the-corgiat-building-near-pioneer-square/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.3338,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1900 the Corgiat Building lost its cornice and identifying sign to the 1949 earthquake.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/hotel-main-then-mr.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Butler did it!","d":"2017-01-21","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/01/21/seattle-now-then-the-butler-did-it/","lat":47.6034,"lon":-122.3323,"c":"place_approx","x":"Adding a sixth floor to its first five in 1903, the Hotel Butler entered a thirty-year run as \"the place\" for dancing in the Rose Room, dining at the Butler Grill, and celebrity-mixing in the lobby.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/hotel-butler-nwcor-james-2nd-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Last of Denny Hill, Part 1","d":"2017-01-28","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/01/28/seattle-now-then-the-last-of-denny-hill-part-1/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.368,"c":"place","x":"Looking west (not east) on Battery Street from Seventh Avenue, approaching the end of the last of Denny Hill's six regrade reductions. The dirt was carried to Elliott Bay on conveyor belts like the two shown here.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/battery-e-fm-7th-1930-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Last of Denny Hill, Part 2","d":"2017-02-04","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/02/04/seattle-now-then-the-last-of-denny-hill-part-2/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"(click to enlarge photos) THEN 1: Recorded on April 14, 1928, about sixth months before the Denny Hill Regrade No. 2 began, the last of the scarred Denny Hill rises to the right of Fifth Avenue. Denny School (1884) tops the hill at the northeast corner of Battery Street and Fifth Avenue. On the horizon, at center, Queen Anne Hill is topped by its namesake high school, and on the right of the panor","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/denny-hill-regrade-no-2-april-16-1928.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Seattle’s First Chinatown","d":"2017-02-11","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/02/11/seattle-now-then-seattles-first-chinatown/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The Phoenix Hotel on Second Avenue, for the most part to the left of the darker power pole, and the Chin Gee Hee Building, behind it and facing Washington Street to the right, were both built quickly after Seattle's Great Fire of June 6, 1889.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/seattles-first-chinatown-then-2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Looking East from Ninth and Pike","d":"2017-02-18","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/02/18/seattle-now-then-looking-east-from-ninth-and-pike/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"This 1939 glimpse east from Ninth Avenue follows Pike Street to the end of the about three-quarter mile straight climb it makes on its run from the Pike Place Market to its first turn on Capitol Hill. [CLICK to ENLARGE and so on]","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/pike-lk-e-fm-9-then-mr-1940.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Two Marches (on 4th Avenue)","d":"2017-02-25","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/02/25/seattle-now-then-two-marches-on-4th-avenue/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Lawton Gowey looks north through the tail of the 1957 Independence Day Parade on Fourth Avenue as it proceeds south through the intersection with Pike Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/4th-ave-parade-pike-st-7-4-1957-then-mr2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Big Clock in Big Snow, 1916","d":"2017-03-04","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/03/04/seattle-now-then-big-clock-in-big-snow-1916/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"The Big Snow of 1916 trims two jewelers' clocks on the west side of Second Avenue, north of Marion Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/big-clock-in-big-snow-of-1912-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Our Lady of Good Help","d":"2017-03-11","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/03/11/seattle-now-then-our-lady-of-good-help/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"On the left, most likely the first photograph of Father Prefontaine's Our Lade of Good Help at the northeast corner of Washington Street and Third Avenue, and, on the right, a late and perhaps last record of the enlarged sanctuary.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/our-lady-of-good-help-twice.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Our Lady of Good Help – Part 2","d":"2017-03-18","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/03/18/seattle-now-then-our-lady-of-good-help-part-2/","lat":47.6027,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Our Lady of Good Help at the southeast corner of Jefferson Street and Fifth Avenue, its second home from 1905 to 1949, was abandoned following a shifting of its foundation after a heavy rain.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/our-lady-of-good-help-5th-jeff-then-mr.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"East Olive Way, Sept. 21, 1938","d":"2017-03-25","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/03/25/seattle-now-then-east-olive-way-sept-21-1938/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"The busy apartment house development on Capitol Hill in the early 20th Century included the Belvedere Vista Apartment, on the left of this 1938 look northeast on East Olive Way. Filling its flatiron block, the Belvedere Vista is also bordered by E. Olive Place and Melrose Ave. East. While the Belvedere Vista does not appear on the 1912 Baist Real Estate Map, it is listed in the 1915 Polk City Dire","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/e-olive-way-sept-21-1938-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Broadway and Republican","d":"2017-04-01","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/04/01/seattle-now-then-broadway-and-republican/","lat":47.6253,"lon":-122.3222,"c":"place","x":"The billboard for Karo Syrup is the intended subject in this early 1930s cityscape at the Capitol Hill intersection of Broadway and Republican Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/broadway-republican-secor-mr-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Armour Building","d":"2017-04-08","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/04/08/seattle-now-then-the-armour-building/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"The Chicago packer's J. Ogden Armour's namesake building at the northeast corner of Third avenue and Jackson Street, ca. 1912.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/armour-building-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Queen City Florist at 13th & Union","d":"2017-04-15","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/04/15/seattle-now-then-queen-city-florist-at-13th-union/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.326,"c":"place","x":"I speculate that in order to lift the photographer for this elevated look south over Union Street and the nearly new Queen City Floral Co.'s nursery, the photograph was recorded from the top of a Madison Street Cable Car. In the mid 1890s, the German-born John Holze got his Seattle start as a florist-gardener for the Madison Street Cable Railway Company. His residence then was at Madison Park.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/queen-city-florest-comp-then-mr.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Independence Day at 3rd and Yesler","d":"2017-04-22","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/04/22/seattle-now-then-independence-day-at-3rd-and-yesler/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"Looking east up Yesler Way with the Seattle Police Department during the city's celebrations for the 1899 Independence Day.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/july-4-1899-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Lower Roosevelt Way, 1940","d":"2017-04-29","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/04/29/seattle-now-then-lower-roosevelt-way/","lat":47.677,"lon":-122.317,"c":"place","x":"Roosevelt Way in 1940, looking north from E. 41st Street. (The named direction was later changed to N.E. 41st. Street)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/roosevelt-way-no-fm-41st-1940-mr-then.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Westlake, ‘The Big Funnel’","d":"2017-05-05","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/05/05/seattle-now-then-westlake-the-big-funnel/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"A few of the landmarks revealed in this mid-twenties look north from the roof of the Medical Dental Building include Queen Anne High School, \"Wilson's Wood Row\" of unused WW1 freighters camped in Lake Union, the Seattle Gas Company's big holder at 9th and Republican, the Ford Assembly Plant and Denny Park. Can you find them?","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/image001.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"North End of Fremont Bridge","d":"2017-05-13","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/05/13/seattle-now-then-north-end-of-fremont-bridge/","lat":47.648,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"(click to enlarge photos) NOW: An uncredited photographer looks north on Fremont Street from its original intersection with Ewing Street (N. Northlake Way). NOW: Members of the Fremont Historical Society pose on the Fremont Bridge, prudently to the side of the busier northbound lane and also well ahead of the traffic advancing south from the 34th Street intersection behind them. Member Judie Clarr","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/fremont-bridge-no-end-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Pier 56","d":"2017-05-19","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/05/19/seattle-now-then-pier-56/","lat":47.6055,"lon":-122.3424,"c":"place","x":"The Japanese barque, Nippon Maru, visited Seattle during the summer of 1965. Here it shares the slip on the south side of Pier 56 with vessels of the Seattle Harbor Tours.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pier-56-w-nippon-maru-then-6-29-65-b.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Ice Arena","d":"2017-05-27","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/05/27/seattle-now-then-the-ice-arena/","lat":47.6212,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"The Mercer Arts Arena's last hurrah was the exposure of the building's four original front door Gargoyles. Two were saved and removed.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/ice-arena-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Sea View Hall","d":"2017-06-03","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/06/03/seattle-now-then-sea-view-hall/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"In 1954, the then 50-year-old Sea View Hall featured swinging, wooden \"logoglyph\"-style letters to proclaim its name, next to a large television antenna. (Photo from MOHAI, Seattle Post-Intelligencer Collection, 1986.5.9199.1.)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/sea-view-hall-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Ballard Beginnings","d":"2017-06-10","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/06/10/seattle-now-then-ballard-beginnings/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"Looking south – we propose – from near the corner of Ballard's NW 58th Street and 22nd Avenue NW, circa 1889.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/early-balard-then-copy.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Alley That Became I-5","d":"2017-06-17","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/06/17/seattle-now-then-the-alley-that-became-i-5/","lat":47.6173,"lon":-122.3478,"c":"place_approx","x":"Everything here is terminal. When Werner Lenggenhager recorded this section of Melrose Place N. in the mid-1950s he understood that soon after – in five years or ten – it would be transformed into the Seattle Freeway. It was especially revealing to find the tall hillside home, here on the left, in an aerial photograph, also from the mid-1950s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/wl-country-rd-2-to-d-way-55-then-jpg.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Mysterious Dance at Olive and Terry","d":"2017-06-24","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/06/24/seattle-now-then-mysterious-dance-at-olive-and-terry/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place_approx","x":"For some unrecorded reason in the late 1920s, I figure, an unnamed photographer was attracted to the diverse urban clutter to the sides of this intersection of Olive Street (upper-left) and Terry Avenue (lower-left.) [Courtesy, Lawton Gowey]","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/reformed-presby-olilve-terry-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Coo Coo Flats","d":"2017-07-01","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/07/01/seattle-now-then-coo-coo-flats/","lat":47.6034,"lon":-122.33,"c":"place_approx","x":"On December 6, 1962, Frank Shaw recorded this look north from Cherry Street. The doomed structures that remained for only a few more weeks were in the chosen path for the Seattle Freeway. The block-wide line between Sixth and Seventh Avenues was chosen in the 1950s for the construction of Interstate-5's concrete landscape through the business district.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/coo-coo-flats-then-copy.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Fifth Avenue Regrade, 1911","d":"2017-07-08","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/07/08/seattle-now-then-a-fifth-avenue-regrade-1911/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Beginning in 1876, Seattle's downtown streets were all regraded, starting on First Avenue (aka Front Street). Here, thirty-five years later in 1911, the cutting has reached Fifth Avenue at Cherry Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/5th-cherry-regrade-then-2.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Margaret Denny’s First Hill Home","d":"2017-07-15","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/07/15/seattle-now-then-margaret-dennys-first-hill-home/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place","x":"The Margaret and Mary Ann Denny home spent its waning years, first in 1925 as The Chateau with rentable \"accommodations for particular people in the most beautiful residence on First Hill,\" followed in 1926-27 as The Hospitality Club, advertised as \"for young business girls and students.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/denny-home-university-boren-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"‘The City is More Than Human’","d":"2017-07-22","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/07/22/seattle-now-then-the-city-is-more-than-human/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place","x":"Ballard dairy farmer Jess Jensen poses with four of his milch cows on 8th Avenue Northwest, near its intersection with NW 58th Street. The subject looks north.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/the-city-is-more-then-human-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Blyth Barn on Squak Slough","d":"2017-07-29","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/07/29/seattle-now-then-the-blyth-barn-on-squak-slough/","lat":47.73,"lon":-122.16,"c":"place","x":"Looking north over Squak Slough (aka the Sammamish River) and the Blyth farm ca. 1900. The barn stood near what is now the tee for the 18th hole of the Wayne Golf Course.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/the-blyth-barn-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Gatewood School","d":"2017-08-05","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/08/05/seattle-now-then-the-gatewood-school/","lat":47.6678,"lon":-122.3842,"c":"place_approx","x":"Opened in 1910 to 268 students in grades 1 to 8, school architect Edgar Blair's Gatewood Elementary School was awarded landmark status by the city in 1988.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/gatewood-school-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"John Stamets’ Pike Place Market Portrait","d":"2017-08-12","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/08/12/seattle-now-then-john-stamets-pike-place-market-portrait/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Most likely many readers will remember – and some can also stand on their proof – when the Market paved its Arcade with new \"name tiles\" funded by the thousands of preservationist that purchased them. Note the banner promoting the $35 tiles. Stamets recorded this on May 25, 1986 during the Market Street Fair.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/stamets-corner-building-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Swedish Hospital, 1929","d":"2017-08-19","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/08/19/seattle-now-then-swedish-hospital-1929/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.321,"c":"place","x":"Looking southwest from Marion Street along Summit Avenue into the campus of the Swedish Hospital in the late 1920s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/swedish-hosp-summit-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The ‘Empire Builder’s’ Bust","d":"2017-08-26","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/08/26/seattle-now-then-the-empire-builders-bust/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place_approx","x":"Situated first at the center of the Alaska Yukon Pacific's Klondike Circle, James J. Hill's monumental likeness was backed by the Exposition's Sweden Building. The view looks to the West.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/james-hill-statue-ayp.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Dump at Dexter and Aloha","d":"2017-09-02","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/09/02/seattle-now-then-a-dump-at-dexter-and-aloha/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"A city dump at the southwest corner of Lake Union in 1915. (Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/dexter-aloha-then2.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Two Founders on Main Street","d":"2017-09-09","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/09/09/seattle-now-then-two-founders-on-main-street/","lat":47.6001,"lon":-122.33427,"c":"addr","x":"Posing for a Post-Intelligencer photographer, Martin Johanson pauses from his daily chores of keeping the Millionair Club he founded fit and clean ca. 1925.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/millionair-club-98-main-st-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Onarga Apartments","d":"2017-09-16","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/09/16/seattle-now-then-the-onarga-apartments/","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.3185,"c":"place","x":"This week's \"then\" features another tax assessor's photo rescued a half-century ago from the department's rubbish by Stan Unger, then a preservation-sensitive young employee. The flats here face Seventh Avenue between Spring and Seneca streets.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/onarga-apts-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Parking 15 Cents","d":"2017-09-23","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/09/23/seattle-now-then-parking-15-cents/","lat":47.6087,"lon":-122.3216,"c":"place_approx","x":"The two apartments houses rising on the east side of 8th Avenue and above the parking lot office are the Van Siclen Apartments (1911) on the left, and the Alfaretta Aparments (1918) beside it on the northeast corner with Seneca Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/parking-15cents-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Denny Hotel","d":"2017-09-30","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/09/30/seattle-now-then-the-denny-hotel/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place","x":"The Denny aka Washington Hotel on the double-block of Denny Hill's southern summit. The view looks southwest over the intersection of Virginia Street and Fourth Avenue.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/denny-hotel-fm-4th-virginia-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Lake Union Logs","d":"2017-10-07","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/10/07/seattle-now-then-lake-union-logs/","lat":47.642,"lon":-122.335,"c":"place","x":"Looking north on Lake Union from some unidentified off-shore prospect near where Galer Street reached the Westlake Trestle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/westlake-logs-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Camlin Hotel","d":"2017-10-14","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/10/14/seattle-now-then-the-camlin-hotel/","lat":47.6132,"lon":-122.3306,"c":"place","x":"When it was new in the 1920s, the Camlin Hotel was described as \"Seattle's aristocrat among residential hotels.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/camlin-hotel-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Finding Kikisoblu (aka ‘Princess Angeline’)","d":"2017-10-22","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/10/22/seattle-now-and-then-princess-angeline-at-home/","lat":47.6128,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place_approx","x":"Pioneer Seattle photographer Frank LaRoche's revealing record of Princess Angeline's last home is also stocked with clues for finding its location. We have put helpful aids – like a map – in the blog pauldorpat.com. [Courtesy, the Museum of History and Industry]","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/1-princess-angeline-featured-home-laroche-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The UW South Campus – Oars and Oceanography","d":"2017-10-28","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/10/28/seattle-now-then-the-uw-south-campus-oars-and-oceanography/","lat":47.65,"lon":-122.305,"c":"place","x":"Following the Alaska Yukon Pacific Exposition on the U.W. Campus, the AYP'S Tokio Café was converted into a crew house for the University's already popular rowing crews.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/portage-bay-north-shore-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Church on the Corner (of Boren & Pine)","d":"2017-11-04","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/11/04/seattle-now-then-the-church-on-the-corner-of-boren-pine/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.327,"c":"place","x":"In 1938, the likely year of this tax photo, the First Swedish Methodist Church at the north east corner of Boren Avenue and Pine Street was one of several Protestant congregations in the greater Cascade Neighborhood that were built around Scandenavian immigrant communities.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/church-on-the-corner-then-b.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Olympia Beer on the Waterfront","d":"2017-11-11","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/11/11/seattle-now-then-olympia-beer-on-the-waterfront/","lat":47.6062,"lon":-122.3406,"c":"place","x":"Nearly new, the Holden Warehouse on the left, and the bottling plant for Olympia Beer each take half of the block on the east side of Railroad Avenue between Virginia and Pine Streets.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/olympia-brewery-cannery-then-2.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Swedish Club","d":"2017-11-18","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/11/18/seattle-now-then-the-swedish-club/","lat":47.61331,"lon":-122.33348,"c":"addr","x":"The first \"permanent home for the Swedish Club at 1627 Eighth Avenue – between Pine and Olive Streets – was built in 1901-2. After a half-century in Seattle's greater-retail neighborhood, the Club moved to its abiding home on Dexter Avenue overlooking Lake Union from Queen Anne Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/swedish-club-on-8th-ave-1938-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Queen Anne’s Scenic Conkling Place","d":"2017-11-25","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/11/25/seattle-now-then-queen-annes-scenic-conkling-place/","lat":47.636,"lon":-122.356,"c":"place","x":"This wide-angled panorama sights south on Queen Anne Hill from the corner of Conkling Place West and West Bertona Street. On the far left the Fremont bascule bridge is up and open.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/queen-anne-park-addition-then3.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Kalakala at Low Tide","d":"2017-12-02","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/12/02/seattle-now-then-the-kalakala-at-low-tide/","lat":47.6022,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"Frank Shaw's 1960's stern-end exposure of the Kalakala, \"the world's first streamlined ferry.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Kalakala-color-at-dock-looking-good-Shaw-THEN.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Grading Fremont","d":"2017-12-09","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/12/09/seattle-now-then-grading-fremont/","lat":47.651,"lon":-122.35,"c":"place","x":"Looking West circa 1911 from Fremont's bridge to the improved Northern Pacific Railroad's double-track line on the left, and work-in-progress on raising Ewing Avenue twenty feet with fill behind a new concrete retaining wall.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Northgate-Santa-detail.png&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Husky Stadium, 1920","d":"2017-12-16","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/12/16/seattle-now-then-husky-stadium/","lat":47.6505,"lon":-122.3013,"c":"place","x":"The Husky Stadium's basic horseshoe bleachers were barely completed in time for the transcontinental visit of the Dartmouth College team on Nov. 27, 1920.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Husky-Stadium-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Wallingford Call","d":"2017-12-23","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2017/12/23/seattle-now-then-wallingford-call/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"Looking east through Wallingford's central intersection of N. 45th Street and Wallingford Avenue in 1925.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/WALLINGFORD-CALL-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Golden Potlatch Parade, 1911","d":"2018-01-06","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/01/06/seattle-now-then-golden-potlatch-parade-1911/","lat":47.6147,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place_approx","x":"A Golden Potlatch parade from 1911","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Potlatch-parade-1911THEN-copy.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Polson Building Fire, 1974","d":"2018-01-13","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/01/13/seattle-now-then-polson-building-fire-1974/","lat":47.6071,"lon":-122.3382,"c":"place","x":"The Alaskan Way Viaduct side of the Polson Building on Columbia Street during its 1974 fire. Photographed by Frank Shaw","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Polson-Bldg-Fire-6-14-74-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Poulsbo’s Front Street","d":"2018-01-20","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/01/20/seattle-now-then-poulsbos-front-street/","lat":47.7321,"lon":-122.6432,"c":"place","x":"Poulsbo's Front Street in the 1920s.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/6-12-Poulsbo-Front-St.-aux.-sepia-X.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Winslow Ferry Terminal, ca. 1950","d":"2018-01-27","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/01/27/seattle-now-then-the-winslow-ferry-terminal-ca-1950/","lat":47.6228,"lon":-122.518,"c":"place","x":"The gated ticket booths, posing here ca. 1950 at the Bainbridge Island Ferry Terminal, stand much closer to the landing ferries than now.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Winslow-Ferry-Terminal-ca50-Ellis-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Inside Dexter Horton’s Bank, 1882","d":"2018-02-03","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/02/03/seattle-now-then-inside-dexter-hortons-bank-1882/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.334,"c":"place","x":"The bank's namesake president, Dexter Horton, somehow missed this 1882 portrait of bank employees and officers. Horton may have been enjoying a president's leisure – perhaps duck-hunting. Surely he was not golfing, the sport that first reached Seattle in the mid 1890s on a converted Wallingford cow pasture. [CLICK to ENLARGE]","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Dexter-Hotron-Bank-interior-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Cornish School Construction, 1921","d":"2018-02-10","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/02/10/seattle-now-then-cornish-school-construction-1921/","lat":47.6178,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Cornish School under construction in 1921 at its new campus at Harvard Avenue and E. Roy Street.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Cornish-construction-THEN-.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Parades at 4th and Pine","d":"2018-02-17","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/02/17/seattle-now-then-parades-at-4th-and-pine/","lat":47.6175,"lon":-122.347,"c":"place","x":"Fewer than fifty years before this 1953 parade was photographed on Fourth Avenue, the block between Pine and Stewart Streets negotiated, barely, one of the steepest streets on Denny Hill.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/1-Westlake-from-Josh-Green-or-predessor-more-likley-WS-WEB.jpg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"St. Francis Hall","d":"2018-02-24","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/02/24/seattle-now-then-st-francis-hall/","lat":47.6097,"lon":-122.3192,"c":"place","x":"From 1891 to 1909, the St. Francis Hall faced Spring Street on the second lot west of Sixth Avenue. The Hall was photographed by the Norwegian immigrant Anders Wilse in 1900 only weeks before he returned to Norway for photographic work that made him a Norwegian national treasure.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/St.-Francis-Hall-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"3rd and Pike Looking East, ca. 1903","d":"2018-03-03","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/03/03/seattle-now-then-3rd-and-pike-looking-east-ca-1903/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"Sarah Sophia Frye Bass, a pioneer Denny family granddaughter grew up on Pike Street in the 1870s. In her oft-read book Pigtail Days In Old Seattle, published in 1938, she noted \"it is today the busiest street in town by actual traffic counts.\"","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Pike-E.-fm-3rd-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Ave Trolley, ca. 1939","d":"2018-03-10","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/03/10/seattle-now-then-the-ave-trolley-ca-1939/","lat":47.6614,"lon":-122.3127,"c":"place","x":"On University Way, ca 1939, when the 4300 block on The Ave was the busiest book block in Seattle.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/AVE-TROLLEY-Ca.-1939-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Pioneer Place Welcome, 1908","d":"2018-03-17","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/03/17/seattle-now-then-a-pioneer-place-welcome-1908/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.338,"c":"place","x":"The prospect looks east on Yesler Way through its intersection with First Avenue. James Street enters the five-star corner left-of-center.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/PIONEER-PLACE-08-Great-White-Fleet-THEN-2.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"An Elks Carnival, 1902","d":"2018-03-24","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/03/24/seattle-now-then-an-elks-carnival-1902/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"An unidentified photographer looks southeast through the intersection of Third Avenue and Union Street during Seattle's first-ever multi-day summer festival, the Elks 1902 Seattle Street Fair and Carnival.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Elks-Carnival-Arch-1902-3Union-seCor-THEN-copy.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Dairy Men at Dreamland","d":"2018-03-31","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/03/31/seattle-now-then-dairy-men-at-dreamland/","lat":47.61139,"lon":-122.33172,"c":"addr","x":"Thanks to Larry Lowry who long ago shared with me this grand photograph of Dreamland. He noted, \"My grandfather, Waverly Mairs, was the ice cream maker at the old Seattle Dairy.\" Perhaps, Waverly is also in the photograph.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Dreamland-5-TEAMS-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Mill Street, ca. 1887","d":"2018-04-07","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/04/07/seattle-now-then-mill-street-ca-1887/","lat":47.602,"lon":-122.329,"c":"place","x":"A pre-1889 Great Fire look east on Mill Street (Yesler Way) from the west side of Commercial Street (First Ave. South).","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Mill-St.-THEN-CA-1887.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Market’s Front Door","d":"2018-04-14","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/04/14/seattle-now-then-the-markets-front-door/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"By 1931, the likely year for this photo looking east on Pike Street from the Pike Place Market, this intersection had been loved for a quarter-century as the market's front door. (Photo courtesy Museum of History & Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Pike-St-ca.-1930-fm-Pike-Market-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Savery Cherries","d":"2018-04-21","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/04/21/seattle-now-then-savery-cherries/","lat":47.6553,"lon":-122.3035,"c":"place","x":"The southwest end of the University of Washington's Savery Hall, still under construction, on the left, was completed in 1920, also a likely year for the photograph.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/UW-QUAD-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Second and Columbia, 1886","d":"2018-04-28","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/04/28/seattle-now-then-5/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.337,"c":"place","x":"Both of this week's featured photographs were recorded from the same elevated prospect, but by different professional photographers: T. E. Peiser and D.R. Judkins. The latter's can be identified by the studio sign that rises high, far left on a post at the southwest corner of Second Avenue and Columbia Street. Both photos date from 1886, and include different cues: the one of uniformed Knights of ","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Peiser-Knights-of-Pitheus-band-2ave.-b..jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Seattle Seven On the Courthouse Steps","d":"2018-05-05","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/05/05/seattle-now-then-the-seattle-seven-on-the-courthouse-steps/","lat":47.6068,"lon":-122.3324,"c":"place_approx","x":"At the Federal Courthouse on February 17, 1970. By and Courtesy of Doyal Gudgel Sr. and Jr. THEN: Still at the Courthouse, on April 17, 1970. By and Courtesy of Gudgel Sr. and Jr.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Cop-guarding-shatter-Court-House-door.-WEB.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Hamilton in Georgetown","d":"2018-05-12","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/05/12/seattle-now-then-the-hamilton-in-georgetown/","lat":47.547,"lon":-122.322,"c":"place","x":"A stately side of Georgetown's business district, ca. 1920. (Museum of History and Industry)","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Georgetown-THE-Hamilton-Then-.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Spring Street Regrade, 1906-07","d":"2018-05-19","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/05/19/seattle-now-then-the-spring-street-regrade-ca-1906/","lat":47.60465,"lon":-122.33853,"c":"addr","x":"The 1906-7 regrades on Seattle's Second and Third Avenues required grade changes on the streets that crossed them as well. Here Spring Street is being lowered to fit the new grades at its intersections with the avenues.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Spring-Street-Regrade-THEN..jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Where Rails Meet Sails – An 1884 view from Beacon Hill","d":"2018-05-26","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/05/26/seattle-now-then-where-rails-meet-sails-an-1884-view-from-beacon-hill/","lat":47.578,"lon":-122.311,"c":"place","x":"Seattle pioneer photographer Theo E. Peiser's mid-1880s panorama of pioneer Seattle when it was still awash in the tidelands south of King Street. One prominent landmark that our \"then\" and \"now\" share is the Magnolia Peninsula.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/City-fm-Beacon-Hill-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Leland Hotel at Pike and Post","d":"2018-06-02","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/06/02/seattle-now-then-the-leland-hotel-at-pike-and-post/","lat":47.6088,"lon":-122.3402,"c":"place","x":"The Leland Hotel survives – although with many changes – as a market corner stone where Pike Place begins at the foot of Pike Street. One of the earliest adjustments cut away its east façade with and for the 1906-7 development – at an angle – of Pike Place. .","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Hotel-Leland-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"A Denny Home at 3rd and Union","d":"2018-06-09","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/06/09/seattle-now-then-a-denny-home-at-3rd-and-union/","lat":47.609,"lon":-122.3354,"c":"place","x":"Built in 1869 by Seattle pioneer Carson Boren at the southeast corner of Third Avenue and Union Street, the charming structure was home for Carson's mother Sarah Denny and her second husband John Denny, the father of Seattle founders Arthur and David Denny.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/J.-Denny-Home-3rd-Union-nwC-THEN.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"The Northwest Folklife Festival","d":"2018-06-23","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/06/23/seattle-now-then-the-northwest-folklife-festival/","lat":47.6212,"lon":-122.349,"c":"place","x":"Members of the Love Israel Family performing beside the Flag Plaza Pavilion (note the sign upper-left) at the Folklife Festival on May 30, 1976.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Love-Family-1-%40-Folk-Fest.-5-30-1976.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Maryland Place in West Seattle","d":"2018-06-30","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/06/30/seattle-now-then-maryland-place-in-west-seattle/","lat":47.59304,"lon":-122.38339,"c":"addr","x":"The 1937/8 tax assessor's photo of 4013 Maryland Place, precariously built on the east slope of West Seattle's Duwamish Head.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/MARYLAND-Pl.-4013-sw-Maryland-Place-1938-THEN-copy.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"},{"t":"Marion Street Looking East through Western Ave, ca 1905","d":"2018-07-07","u":"https://pauldorpat.com/2018/07/07/seattle-now-then-marion-street-looking-east-through-western-ave-ca-1905/","lat":47.6103,"lon":-122.30747,"c":"addr","x":"Looking east on a Marion Street showing several delivery wagons with their often affectionately matched teams of horse power.","i":"https://i0.wp.com/pauldorpat.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/EAST-on-Marion-across-WESTERN-then.jpeg&#038;ssl=1"}];